export const MYOW_CONTENT = "Making Your Own Weather™\n\nBob Goodwin\n\nCopyright © 2026 Decima, LLC. All rights reserved.\n\nMaking Your Own Weather is a trademark of Decima, LLC.\n\nNo part of this publication may be reproduced, distributed, or transmitted in any form\n\nwithout the prior written permission of the publisher.\n\nPublished by Decima, LLC • career.club\n\nThe information in this book is intended for educational purposes only. It does not constitute\n\nprofessional career, legal, or financial advice. Results will vary based on individual circumstances,\n\neffort, and market conditions.\n\nTable of Contents\n\nIntroduction: Making Your Own Weather\n\nAbout the Author\n\nLesson 1 — Keeping an Even KEEL\n\nLesson 2 — Community: Your Job Search Is a Team Sport\n\nLesson 3 — The 4 C’s: Don’t Air Bad Commercials\n\nLesson 4 — Bake a Cake and the Cherry on Top\n\nLesson 5 — Your Resume: Adjectives Are Not Accomplishments\n\nLesson 6 — Networking: The Most Powerful Question\n\nLesson 7 — Direct Outreach: Making Your Own Weather\n\nLesson 9 — STAR: The Company Is Hiring Your Brain\n\nLesson 9B — People Hire People\n\nLesson 10 — Remixing and SCOPE: One Story, Many Dimensions\n\nLesson 11 — Closing the Deal: Negotiating\n\nA Final Word\n\nAppendix: Resources and Further Reading\n\nAbout the Author\n\nBob Goodwin is the founder and President of Career Club, a job search coaching community he founded in 2021 to help professionals in transition find their next role with more clarity, confidence, and strategy. Through Career Club Corner, his free weekly coaching call, he has helped thousands of job seekers navigate one of the most challenging experiences in professional life.\n\nA veteran of the technology, professional services, and data analytics industries, Bob has held senior commercial roles at Xerox, Dun & Bradstreet, EY, and Numerator, and has spent decades at the intersection of talent, leadership, and business growth. He is an executive coach, a LinkedIn Top Voice, an Executive Advisor to SHRM — the world’s leading authority on work, workers, and the workplace — and co-host of The Work Wire with SHRM CEO Johnny C. Taylor Jr. He serves on the board and programming committee of CincySHRM and is a member of the HBR Advisory Council.\n\nBob’s podcast, Career Club, features candid conversations with some of the world’s most respected business leaders — including C-suite executives from companies like P&G, Mastercard, and Merck — on the topics of leadership, career, and professional reinvention.\n\nMaking Your Own Weather™ is his first book.\n\ncareer.club\n\nIntroduction: Making Your Own Weather\n\nI didn’t set out to write a job search book. I set out to find a job.\n\nA number of years ago I was a partner in a market research firm in Cincinnati. For reasons I won’t relitigate here, the partnership didn’t work out and I found myself on the outside looking in. As the sole breadwinner with four kids and college tuitions bearing down on me, a prolonged job search was not an option I could afford, financially or psychologically.\n\nI was upset. I was frustrated. Metaphorically speaking, it felt cold, wet, and deeply unpleasant. But I made a decision early on that I was not going to have a pity party about the weather. The weather was what it was. What I could control was what I did about it.\n\nI kept coming back to something Stephen Covey writes about in The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People, specifically the distinction between your circle of concern and your circle of control. Your circle of concern is everything that worries you: the market, the economy, the partnership that fell apart, the timing, the competition. Your circle of control is smaller and more powerful: your attitude, your actions, your choices about how to show up every single day.\n\nMy circle of concern was full of clouds, wind, and rain. My circle of control was the only place I could actually do anything. So I did the only thing I knew how to do. I went into sales mode. I got creative, stayed positive, and got active. I made my own weather.\n\nIt worked. And over the twenty years since, I have had the privilege of helping thousands of job seekers do the same: find a plan, find a purpose, and find their way to the other side of one of the hardest professional experiences most people will ever go through.\n\nThe process I used then, refined through those thousands of conversations and coaching sessions, is what this book contains. It is not theoretical. It is not generic. Every framework, every tool, every piece of advice in these pages has been tested in the real conditions of a real search by real people with real stakes.\n\nYou may be reading this because your situation feels a lot like mine did. The stakes are high. The timeline feels impossible. The weather, metaphorically speaking, is terrible.\n\nGood. You’re exactly who this book was written for.\n\nLet’s go make some weather.\n\nWhat This Course Is\n\nMaking Your Own Weather is a complete job search system, from the mindset you need before you start to the negotiation conversation at the finish line. It is built around five sections that follow a deliberate sequence. Each section builds on the one before it, and skipping ahead is tempting but costly.\n\nThe five sections are:\n\nAttitude — Before tactics, you need a foundation. Your attitude is the keel that runs under the entire journey. No matter how well-built the boat, it will capsize without it. The attitude lessons cover keeping an even keel through the emotional turbulence of a search, and why community makes every part of this better.\n\nPersonal Branding — You are a brand. Before you talk to anyone, you need to know what you are selling. The personal branding lessons cover the 4 C’s, how to synthesize your assets into a compelling value proposition, and how to express that across your resume and LinkedIn profile.\n\nOutreach — Now you buy media. With your message right, you go on air. The outreach lessons cover networking and the direct outreach approach that gives this course its name — going out to create opportunities rather than waiting for them to appear.\n\nInterviewing — Everything before this is preparation. Game day is the interview. The interviewing lessons cover STAR stories, the human dimension of how hiring decisions get made, and how to remix your stories for any interviewer in any context.\n\nNegotiating — You have earned the offer. Now close the deal on the best possible terms. The negotiating lesson covers BATNA, compensation strategy, the full landscape of what is negotiable, and how to handle the conversation with confidence and data.\n\nEach lesson is designed to be read, reflected on, and acted on. The Reflection questions at the end of each lesson are not optional extras. They are the mechanism by which you convert reading into doing. Answer them in writing before moving to the next lesson.\n\nA Note on How to Use This Book\n\nRead it in order, at least the first time. The sections are sequential by design. You cannot negotiate well without having interviewed well. You cannot interview well without knowing your stories. You cannot tell your stories without knowing your brand. You cannot build your brand without the right attitude underneath it.\n\nIf you are in the middle of an active search and need to jump to a specific lesson, do that. But come back and do the full sequence when you can. The cumulative effect is greater than any individual lesson.\n\nOne More Thing\n\nJob search is hard. Not just logistically. Emotionally too. It asks you to sell yourself in a culture that taught you that was impolite. It exposes you to rejection at a time when rejection is the last thing you need. It puts your professional identity under pressure in ways that are genuinely difficult.\n\nI know this because I’ve lived it, and because I’ve sat with thousands of people going through it. The loneliness and frustration are real. So is the resilience I’ve watched people find, including a version I found in myself that I didn’t know was there until I needed it.\n\nTwo authors have shaped how I think about this. Stephen Covey, whose The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People gave me the language of circles of concern and control that runs through this entire course. And Viktor Frankl, the Viennese psychiatrist and Holocaust survivor whose Man’s Search for Meaning is the most important book I have ever read on the subject of finding purpose inside a struggle. I will return to both of them throughout. If you have not read Frankl, I hope this book sends you there. It will change your life.\n\nThat resilience is available to you too. This book is one way to access it.\n\nLet’s get to work.\n\nPART ONE\n\nAttitude\n\nThe keel that runs under the entire journey\n\n—\n\nLesson 1 — Keeping an Even KEEL\n\nBefore we talk about resumes, LinkedIn, networking, or interviewing, before any of it, we need to talk about the one thing that will determine whether any of it works.\n\nYour attitude.\n\nNot in the motivational poster sense. Not “stay positive” and “good things are coming.” Something deeper than that: a fundamental orientation toward what you are going through and what it is capable of producing in you.\n\nYou can have a terrific resume and an unbelievable network. You may be in a field where employers are competing for talent. None of that matters if fear, self-doubt, bitterness, or impatience cloud how you show up. Those feelings will manifest as low activity, ineffective conversations, and decisions made from panic rather than purpose.\n\nBut here is what I want you to hold onto before we go any further: you are not broken. What you are feeling, the confusion, the fear, the exhaustion, the occasional wave of embarrassment or anger, that is what everybody feels. It is the nature of this experience. It does not mean something is wrong with you. It means you are human, and this is hard.\n\nThe first step is to name it and tame it. If you are confused, call it confusion. If you are scared, call it fear. If you are bitter about how things ended, call it bitterness. Naming the emotion is how you begin to take its power away. And once you have named it, you can start to ask: what do I want to do with it?\n\nThat question, what do I want to do with this, is where your power lives.\n\nRecovery vs. Resilience\n\nWhen people think about resilience, they picture a foam ball being squeezed under pressure. You clench it in your fist, it compresses, and when you let go it bounces back to its original shape. We call that resilient. I call it recovery. It got back to where it was. That’s it.\n\nResilience looks different. Think about what happens in weight training. When you put a muscle under resistance, you are actually causing tiny tears in the muscle fiber. It is mildly damaging. But over the days that follow, the muscle rebuilds, and when it rebuilds, it comes back a little bigger and a little stronger than it was before. What would have maxed you out six weeks ago is manageable today.\n\nThat is resilience. Not returning to where you were. Becoming stronger than you were.\n\nThat distinction matters enormously for how you think about what you are going through right now.\n\nJob search is not something to survive until it is over. It is an experience that is actively forming you: building capacity, developing empathy, clarifying what you actually want, revealing what you are made of. The pain is not wasted if you are learning in it and from it. The question worth sitting with is: what do you want this chapter of your life to teach you?\n\nViktor Frankl and the Freedom You Still Have\n\nIn 1942, a Viennese psychiatrist named Viktor Frankl was arrested by the Nazis and sent to the concentration camps. He would spend three and a half years in some of the worst camps in the system, Auschwitz among them. His parents, his siblings, and his pregnant wife all died. He survived.\n\nNot just survived. He emerged from that experience and wrote one of the most important books of the twentieth century: Man’s Search for Meaning. He went on to develop logotherapy, the third great school of Viennese psychology after Freud and Adler, built on the insight that the primary human drive is not pleasure or power but meaning.\n\nI bring up Frankl not to minimize what you are going through by comparison. That would be cheap and wrong. I bring him up because what he discovered in the most extreme possible circumstances is available to you right now, in the circumstances you are in.\n\nThe line I come back to most often: when we are no longer able to change a situation, we are challenged to change ourselves.\n\nYou may not be able to change the job market. You may not be able to change what happened at your last company. You may not be able to change the timeline. But you always, always, get to choose your attitude, and you always get to choose your actions. Nobody can take that away from you.\n\nThat is not a platitude. In Frankl’s case, it was a survival strategy deployed under conditions that make a job search look like a minor inconvenience. He chose to look out for fellow prisoners. He chose to give his last piece of bread to someone who needed it more. He chose to find things to look forward to, reasons to keep going, moments of beauty in the middle of horror.\n\nHe could happen to things. So can you.\n\nThree Ways to Find Meaning Right Now\n\nFrankl identified three paths to meaning that are available to anyone, in any circumstances.\n\nThe first path is creative. What can you build, create, write, teach, or contribute during this time? Volunteering. Mentoring someone earlier in their career. Starting a blog or a newsletter about your area of expertise. Learning something you have always been curious about. Creating is how we remind ourselves that we have something to offer the world right now, not just once we land.\n\nThe second path is experiential. Relationships. Beauty. Small moments of joy that you are probably too busy to notice when you are working full time. Reconnecting with someone you care about who has nothing to do with your job search. Noticing five beautiful things on a walk. Finding joy in small moments.\n\nA lot of people in job search adopt the posture of “no fun until we’re done.” I understand the impulse. This feels serious, and treating it lightly feels like denial. But that posture is counterproductive.\n\nJoy is not a reward for finishing. It is the fuel that keeps you going. You cannot run on empty for months and show up to every conversation as your best self. Fill your cup, not just drain it.\n\nThe third path is attitudinal. This is the most powerful one, and also the hardest. It is the choice to face uncertainty with courage rather than fear. And courage is not the absence of fear. Courage is acknowledging the fear and going forward anyway.\n\nIt is the decision to refuse bitterness even when bitterness feels completely justified. It is choosing to be someone others can lean on, even when you feel like you need someone to lean on yourself.\n\nAnd there is something else worth naming: what you are going through right now is developing a capacity for empathy that you could not have built any other way. There is a difference between sympathy, meaning I feel sorry for you, and empathy, meaning I know how you feel. When you come out the other side of this, you will be able to sit with someone going through something hard and offer them comfort grounded in experience. That makes this not a wasted experience.\n\nThe Story Arc\n\nEvery great story has the same structure. There is a hero. There is a challenge that is bigger than the hero expects. There is a moment, usually around the middle of the story, where the hero seriously doubts herself. Wonders if she has what it takes. Hits what feels like rock bottom just when things seemed like they were finally going in the right direction.\n\nAnd then she overcomes. Not because the circumstances changed, but because she did. She finds what she needed inside herself and uses it, and she fulfills what the story was always building toward.\n\nYou are in a chapter of your story, not at the end of it. The doubt, the difficulty, the uncertainty: that is the middle of the story doing what the middle of stories always does. It is not the conclusion.\n\nHow do you want to write the rest of this?\n\nBecause you have more authorship over that than you probably feel right now. One of the most concrete ways to exercise that authorship is to ask: if I could choose one word to describe the person I want others to see me being through this, how do I want my kids to see me? How do I want my partner to see me? How do I want the people who are watching to see me?\n\nChoose that person. You can. And the people around you are watching, because everybody goes through hard things, nobody gets a pass, and how you carry yourself through yours is one of the most valuable things you will ever model for them.\n\nThe KEEL\n\nA healthy attitude is not just the starting point. It is what you carry with you for the entire journey. Think of it like the keel on a sailboat. Without the keel, even a well-built boat capsizes when the wind picks up or the current shifts. The keel does not stop the weather, it keeps the boat stable through it. The lows can be terrifyingly low. The highs can be deceptively high. Your keel keeps you on course through both.\n\nThe antidote to fear, confusion, and bitterness is a set of four principles simple enough to remember and powerful enough to return to on a hard day. This is the KEEL.\n\nK — Know you will find another job\n\nNot hope. Know. This is a decision you make before the evidence is fully in.\n\nHere is something worth sitting with: you do not need a hundred yeses. You do not need ten. One company, one hiring manager, one offer, and that is the whole game. A company selling products needs to keep adding customers every year. Your quota is one. Everything in this course is designed to help you hit that quota as efficiently and as confidently as possible.\n\nI have worked with job seekers who spent months measuring themselves against numbers they could not control: how many applications went out, how many interviews led to callbacks, what the market was doing. Those numbers are real, but they are not your scorecard. Your scorecard is simple: did you hit your Quota of One?\n\nEverything else is practice.\n\nWhen fear tells you this is not going to end well, recognize it for what it is. Every person who has ever been in a job search has found a job. You will too.\n\nYou only need one yes.\n\nE — Emotional ups and downs are natural\n\nYou will have great days and terrible days. You will have a conversation that feels like a breakthrough and hear nothing for two weeks afterward. You will be absolutely certain that this is the one, and then it will fall through for reasons that had nothing to do with you.\n\nThese swings are not signals about how your search is going. They are the nature of the process. Expecting them in advance takes away much of their power.\n\nA word of warning on the good news specifically: it is easy to take your foot off the gas when something looks promising. Do not. Keep building your pipeline. Keep doing your outreach. Keep the engine running, because the “guaranteed sure thing” falls through more often than anyone expects, and if it is the only thing in motion when it does, you are starting over from a much harder emotional place.\n\nGive yourself grace on the hard days. Refuse to stay anchored to them.\n\nAnd do not get so attached to the good news that you stop doing the work that produced it.\n\nE — Expect the best from yourself and others\n\nShow up prepared. Do the work. Follow through on what you say you will do. And stop opting people out of the opportunity to help you because it feels uncomfortable.\n\nHere is a test: if someone you had not spoken to in seven years called you and said they were in a job search and wondered if you would take a quick call, would you? Of course you would. You would be glad they reached out. The person you have been hesitating to contact would feel exactly the same way. Do not decide for them that they do not want to hear from you.\n\nWhen a search goes on for a while, it is easy to start thinking you are the problem. You are not the problem. This is a hard market, and the fact that it is taking longer than you expected is not a reliable measure of your worth. Stop playing negative tapes. Expect the best from yourself. Extend the same generosity to the people around you.\n\nL — Let the past go\n\nWhatever happened before this search, the layoff, the partnership that dissolved, the reorg that eliminated your role, the manager who brought in their own people, it probably was unfair. You may be completely justified in everything you are feeling about it.\n\nEven justified bitterness is not helping you. The person who is still yelling about their last situation in every networking conversation becomes that person, and no one knows how to help that person, because that person has not yet decided to move forward.\n\nIf you need to vent, do it. With someone who loves you, before you start meeting with people who matter to your search. Grieve it properly. And then let it go.\n\nLetting it go does not mean pretending it did not happen or that it was not painful. It means deciding that what is in front of you matters more than what is behind you.\n\nThe past cannot give you your next job. What is in front of you can.\n\nA Note on Faith\n\nI want to say something here that I say to every Career Club Corner group. I am coming from a Judeo-Christian worldview, and I find enormous comfort in it. If that is not your lane, feel free to move past this section. If it is — or if you are finding that this experience is leading you back toward a faith you had set aside — lean into it. A lot of people discover or rediscover their faith during a job search, because you reach the limit of what your own skills and effort can control, and that clarity is worth something.\n\nWhat I know is this: hope is not optional. You cannot lose your grip on hope and keep going at the level this search requires of you. Wherever your hope comes from, hold onto it.\n\nReflection\n\nHow long have you been in search, and what is the dominant emotion you’ve been carrying? Name it specifically. What would it mean to tame it?\n\nWhere on the recovery-to-resilience spectrum are you right now? Are you trying to get back to where you were, or are you open to the possibility that you could come out of this stronger than you went in?\n\nWhich of Frankl’s three paths to meaning — creative, experiential, attitudinal — is most available to you right now? What is one concrete thing you could do this week in that direction?\n\nWhat is the one word you would choose to describe the person you want others to see you being through this search? Are you being that person today?\n\nWhich of the four KEEL principles is hardest for you right now? What would it look like to act from that principle this week?\n\nIs there something from the past you are still carrying into conversations? What would it actually mean to let it go — not to pretend it did not happen, but to decide that what is in front of you matters more?\n\nLesson 2 — Community: Your Job Search Is a Team Sport\n\nJob search is one of the most isolating experiences a professional can have. When you lose a role, the natural impulse is to withdraw, to pull back from the world, process the hurt and anger in private, and wait until you feel ready to face people again. I understand that impulse completely. The last thing most people want when they are feeling low is to go meet a lot of new people.\n\nThat instinct is exactly backwards.\n\nA friend of mine once described being in job search as feeling like he was living inside a snow globe, stuck in his own small reality while watching the world go on around him through the glass. That image has stayed with me, because I think it captures what prolonged isolation does to a person in search. The world keeps moving. Opportunities surface and disappear. Connections get made. And if you are inside the globe watching it all happen, none of that reaches you.\n\nThere is a story in the Good Book that I think of every time I teach this lesson. A paralyzed man hears that the Teacher is nearby and is healing people. He desperately wants to get to Him, but faces two problems: he cannot walk, and the place is packed with crowds. His friends will not let those obstacles stand. They carry him on a stretcher, get him to the roof of the building, dig a hole through it, and lower him down directly in front of the person he needs to reach. When He sees what these friends have done, He puts the man back on his feet and says He has never seen anything quite like it.\n\nThe man did not get healed because he was exceptional. He got healed because he had people willing to carry him, get creative on his behalf, and refuse to let the crowd stop them.\n\nYour job search is a team sport. And the people around you, if you let them in, will help carry you.\n\nFive Reasons to Be in Community During Your Search\n\nEncouragement\n\nGoing back to what we covered in Lesson 1 on keeping an even keel: there is a lot of rejection on the road to the offer. Some days you will be the one giving encouragement. Some days you will be the one receiving it. Your emotional gas tank runs low during a search, and there is nothing like having someone who understands exactly what you are going through help you bounce back from a disappointment. Not sympathy — empathy. They know how you feel because they are in it too.\n\nNew Ideas\n\nThis is the wisdom of the crowd. I know I do not have all the good ideas, and I suspect you do not either. When we share our stories, our struggles, and our wins with others, we benefit from their experiences and their unique ways of seeing things. One person in the group has a contact you have never heard of. Another has found a tool that changed how they approach outreach. Another has figured out how to frame their background in a way you had not considered for your own. None of that reaches you if you are inside the snow globe.\n\nNetworking\n\nThis is probably the most obvious reason people join a job search group, but the counterintuitive truth is worth saying out loud. You are statistically most likely to find your next role through someone you do not know today. Third and fourth degree connections. People traveling in different information circles than the ones you already move in. The Career Club Corner community exists partly for this: a built-in network of people who understand what you are going through, want to help you, and are themselves connected to people you have never met. If you feel like you have burned through your existing network, here is a fresh pond to fish in.\n\nOne important caveat: if you start networking aggressively before you have your message right, it can work against you. Going on air before the commercial is ready is expensive. Get the 4 C’s and your Tell Me About Yourself story in place first, then go wide. We cover all of that in the Personal Branding section.\n\nAccountability\n\nThis is one of the most powerful and most underrated aspects of being in a group. There is a world of difference between a good intention and a good behavior. When I tell the group I am going to send five proactive outreach emails this week and reach out to three new contacts, I will do it, because I do not want to show up next week having not done it. Left entirely to my own devices, I can come up with excellent reasons to delay. But when I have made a commitment to people I respect, that changes the calculus entirely.\n\nFind one or two people you click with and hold each other to your weekly commitments. That relationship is the difference between moving and standing still.\n\nResources\n\nA good job search community will expose you to expertise and tools you would not have found on your own: guest speakers, resume writers, LinkedIn specialists, career coaches, AI tools, assessment instruments, and the collective knowledge of everyone in the room. No one person has access to all the good resources. A community does.\n\nA Safe Place to Practice\n\nOne thing the Career Club Corner community has become that I did not fully anticipate when I started it is a practice environment. One of our members put it well: it is a place to make networking mistakes safely, get honest feedback, and train before the stakes are real. When you practice your Tell Me About Yourself here, when you stumble on a word and someone points it out, when you try a new framing and it does not land, those are reps you do not have to burn in a live interview. Use the community that way. It is one of the most underutilized gifts available to you.\n\nTwo Warnings\n\nThe first is the pity party. Sitting around commiserating feels like community but it is not. It burns time and energy that could be going somewhere. Venting for a few minutes before you get to work is human and fine. Making it the agenda is not. If the group’s primary activity is validating each other’s grievances, find a different group.\n\nThe second is fake LinkedIn community, spending most of your day trading encouraging posts and commenting on other people’s content instead of doing the actual work of the search. It feels better than watching television, and it is about as productive. LinkedIn is a powerful outreach tool. It is not a substitute for the search itself.\n\nHow to Find Your Community\n\nIf you are not already in Career Club Corner, you are welcome here. In most cities there is at least one job search group, often several. A quick search for “job search group” plus your city will give you a head start. LinkedIn uses the same search string. As you are networking, ask people whether they are in a group they have found helpful. Nothing beats a recommendation from someone who has been through it.\n\nIf your former employer provided outplacement services, many outplacement firms offer group settings. That can be another entry point.\n\nDo not do this alone. The camaraderie, shared ideas, networking access, and accountability that come from being in community will fuel your search in ways that going it solo simply cannot.\n\nReflection\n\nHave you been treating your search as a solo project? If so, what has that cost you — in energy, in ideas, in accountability?\n\nWhich of the five benefits of community resonates most with where you are right now in your search?\n\nDo you have an accountability partner? If not, who is one person you could reach out to this week to build that relationship?\n\nAre you using the Career Club Corner networking sheet? If you have registered but not reached out to anyone, who are five people you will contact before next week?\n\nIs your community a place of honest feedback and forward momentum, or has it drifted toward the pity party end of the spectrum?\n\nPART TWO\n\nPersonal Branding\n\nKnow what you are selling before you go on air\n\n—\n\nLesson 3 — The 4 C’s\n\nBefore we go deeper into this work, a note on tools. Throughout this section I will reference four assessments that can help you understand yourself more clearly: Affintus, CliftonStrengths, the Barrett Values Centre Personal Values Assessment, and DiSC. None of them are required. All of them are useful. If you have not completed any yet, start with Affintus, it was built specifically for job seekers and the output is immediately applicable. All four are free or low-cost and are detailed in the Appendix. If you have already taken any of them, pull the reports out now. The work ahead will give you new ways to use what they surfaced.\n\nThink of the past few weeks as your research phase. You have been working on your attitude, building your community, and getting your head right for what comes next. Now we move into something more tangible: the foundation of your personal brand.\n\nBefore you talk to anyone about your search. Before you update your resume. Before you send a single outreach email or pick up the phone to call a former colleague. You need to be able to answer two questions clearly, specifically, and without hesitation.\n\nWhat are you looking for? And why you?\n\nIf you cannot answer those two questions in plain language, everything that follows will be harder than it needs to be. You can stay extraordinarily busy in a job search and make almost no progress, and the reason is usually this: the message is not right.\n\nThink about it like a Super Bowl commercial. The Super Bowl is the most expensive media buy in advertising. Millions of dollars to get your brand in front of the largest television audience of the year. And every year, some companies buy that time with a commercial that is confusing, or forgettable, or just wrong for the brand. All that reach, completely wasted because the creative was not ready.\n\nThe job seeker who is out networking aggressively before they know what they are selling is doing the exact same thing. They are in front of a lot of people. The message is not landing. And unlike a company that can pull a bad ad and regroup, you only get one first impression with each person in your network. Go off air. Get the message right. Then go on air.\n\nThe 4 C’s are the framework I developed to help people get that message right. They are sequential. Each builds on the one before it, and the sequence is not reversible. The four are Convictions, Clarity, Confidence, and Contagious. Convictions lead to Clarity. Clarity leads to Confidence. And Confidence is Contagious. Let me walk you through each one.\n\nConvictions\n\nConvictions are what you actually believe. Not what sounds good in an interview. Not what you think the hiring manager wants to hear. What is actually, genuinely, demonstrably true about you: the things that would still be true if you stripped away your title, your company, your income, and your job description.\n\nThis is the DNA of your personal brand.\n\nAnd unlike a logo or a tagline, it cannot be designed from the outside. It has to be discovered from the inside.\n\nConvictions are made up of five things.\n\nCore values. Values are not the words companies put on their lobby walls. They are the things you would actually fight for. Here is a question worth sitting with: what would you be willing to be fired over?  I was in a role once where my business partner wanted me to show our bank an old accounts receivable report rather than the current one, because the older number made our financial position look stronger. I would not do it. That was a line. That moment of refusal was not a career strategy. It was a value asserting itself.  Your values show up the same way. What makes you angry? When something strikes you as wrong or unfair and you have a visceral reaction, that is not just emotion. That is a value speaking. Something in you knows there is a better way, a more right answer, and you cannot walk past it without saying so.  One test for whether something is a genuine value: could the opposite also be true and viable for someone else? Being a people person is a real value. Being energized by deep, solitary, focused work is equally real. Neither is right or wrong. Both count. That symmetry is how you know you have found a real value rather than a platitude.  Integrity often fails this test, by the way. The opposite of integrity is not a viable alternative for anyone. What you are really pointing to when you say integrity is something more specific: honesty, transparency, accountability. It is worth doing the work to find out which one it actually is for you.\n\nYour why. What do you have a genuine passion for? What are you naturally curious about, the kind of curious where nobody makes you go learn more, you just do? It could be a people group, a technology, an industry, a problem, a way of thinking.  I come from marketing and consumer insights, and what has always lit me up is understanding why people do what they do and how they make decisions. That curiosity is not something I developed strategically. It was just there. And it has shown up in every role I have ever had.  Find yours. Some prompts that help: I believe in. I have a passion for. I am genuinely curious about. What would you read about or learn about even if nobody was paying you to?\n\nYour track record. I accomplished X as measured by Y. These are your receipts. Your documented history of doing the work and getting results.  We will go deep on this in the resume lesson and the STAR story lessons, because the language of business is numbers and adjectives are not accomplishments. At the convictions level, the question is simpler: what have you actually done, and can you point to it? Not in a general sense. Specifically. What did you build, grow, fix, save, or create, and what did it produce? Your track record is evidence of your ability to do the job and do it well.\n\nYour reputation. What do other people say about you? What do people come to you for when something goes wrong or something important needs doing? What have you been told repeatedly:  • In performance reviews • In hallway conversations • In the way colleagues described you to others  Your reputation is the external reflection of your convictions. It is your brand as others experience it. And it is some of the most powerful evidence you have, because it did not come from you. When you can say people consistently come to me when there is a cross-functional problem that nobody can untangle, and you can name three examples, that is a pattern other people have observed and confirmed. That carries real weight.\n\nYour natural wiring. How are you built? These are the durable, human-based qualities that exist entirely independent of your company, your title, your industry, and your compensation. They are how you came from the factory.  The challenge is that many people are either unaware of what these actually are, or they can feel them but cannot put them into words that mean anything to another person. This is where assessments earn their place.  Affintus is an externally validated strengths assessment worth exploring. It surfaces your natural strengths with the vocabulary to describe them clearly, and it is free for job seekers at affintus.com/job-seekers. CliftonStrengths, available at gallup.com/cliftonstrengths, does similar work and introduces a concept I find particularly useful called balconies and basements:  • Your balcony is what a strength looks like when you are at your best, in your element, doing what you are most naturally wired to do. • Your basement is what that same strength looks like when it is overdeveloped or misdirected.  One of my top CliftonStrengths is Strategic. The balcony is real: I am good at seeing the bigger picture, finding patterns in complexity, and connecting dots that are not obviously related. The basement is equally real: I get bored in the weeds. When something becomes highly detailed and granular, I start to disengage, and details can trip me up.  Knowing that is not a weakness to hide. It is self-awareness to demonstrate. When an interviewer asks about your greatest weakness, you can answer with actual self-knowledge behind it rather than the recycled non-answer that everyone sees through.  When you know your natural wiring specifically enough to name it, something shifts in how you talk about your work. You can explain not just what you accomplished but why you were the person who accomplished it. Before the assessment, you knew you were good at building teams. After the assessment, you can say it is because Individualization is one of your top strengths, the ability to see the distinct qualities in each person and arrange them in a way that brings out their best. That specificity is what makes an answer feel real rather than rehearsed.\n\nTake the time to do this work.\n\nThe self-knowledge you build here is the foundation everything else rests on.\n\nClarity\n\nWhen your convictions are in place, clarity follows. Not because someone tells you what to pursue, but because you begin to see which opportunities actually fit and, just as importantly, which ones do not. Clarity is the wisdom of knowing what to say yes to and knowing what to say no to.\n\nThere is not one perfect job out there for you. That framing puts too much pressure on a single outcome and leads people to either freeze or compromise before they should. There are many good jobs for you: roles and companies where your values, your strengths, your track record, and your curiosity would combine into something that works, where you would be good at what they need and care about what they care about.\n\nWhat clarity gives you is the ability to recognize those roles when you encounter them, and equally important, the ability to recognize the ones that are not right for you and say so without apology.\n\nThat second part matters more than people realize. The worst outcome in a job search is taking the wrong job. Either:\n\nYou are back in the market within three months, which costs you all the time you spent plus the time to rebuild momentum, or\n\nYou take the job and Sunday night becomes something you dread. The job pays the bills and quietly poisons the week. You know before the end of the first month that this is not it, but you stay because starting over feels worse.\n\nClarity is what protects you from both outcomes.\n\nHere is where people often make a critical mistake. The natural instinct in a job search is to keep your options open. Cast a wide net. Be available for as many kinds of roles as possible. The logic feels sound: more possibilities means more chances, and more chances means a shorter search. The opposite is true, and understanding why is one of the most important shifts you can make.\n\nWhen you try to be all things to all potential employers, something happens in the mind of the person you are talking to. They want to help you. They do. But to help you, they need to know where to put you. Our brains are not designed for ambiguity. They need to classify information, to find a home for what they are processing.\n\nWhen you give someone a clear, specific answer about what you are looking for, something clicks:\n\nOh, I know exactly who you should talk to.\n\nOh, there is a company doing that kind of work right now.\n\nOh, my brother-in-law is in that space, you should meet him.\n\nBut when the answer is I am really open to a lot of different things, what happens is nothing. They cannot help you because they do not know how. You have ended up in the junk drawer of their mind.\n\nThe things in a junk drawer are not bad things. A junk drawer is full of perfectly useful objects: batteries, rubber bands, twist ties, the spare key to something you cannot quite remember. None of it is worthless. But none of it has a designated place, so none of it gets found when someone goes looking for something specific. That is what happens to the job seeker who can do many things and has not decided which one they are going after. People remember them warmly and cannot think of a single concrete way to help.\n\nThink about Tide. Tide is one of the biggest consumer brands in the world. If someone in brand management at Procter and Gamble walked into a strategy meeting and said our brand equity is cleaning, so why not get into cleaning floors? Cleaning cars? Personal body wash? That person would be shown the door. Tide does not do those things. Tide is the best at what it is best at, which is cleaning clothes. You know exactly what aisle you find it in. You know exactly what you are getting. That clarity is not a limitation. It is the source of the brand’s power.\n\nThe same principle applies to you. Specificity makes you more attractive, not less. When you are clear about what you are looking for and why, you give people a place to put you. You become findable. The people who know you start to encounter things in their week and think of you immediately. That does not happen for the person who is open to anything. It only happens for the person who has done the work to know what they actually want.\n\nOne more thing about clarity: once you have it, you are no longer pretending in interviews. You are no longer trying to guess the right answer and perform a version of yourself you do not quite believe. When someone asks why you want this role, you have a real answer. When they ask why you would be good at it, you have evidence. That shift in your posture, from performance to conviction, is what takes us to the third C.\n\nConfidence\n\nConfidence is evidence-based self-belief.\n\nThat definition took me years to arrive at, and I want to be precise about what it means. It is not walking into a room projecting certainty you do not feel. It is not claiming to be the best candidate for every role. It is pointing to something real. It is the natural result of having done the work in Convictions and Clarity, of having assembled actual evidence of who you are, what you have done, and what you are actually good at.\n\nHere is how that works in practice. When you have done the work, you have receipts:\n\nYour values\n\nYour why\n\nYour track record of specific, quantifiable accomplishments\n\nYour reputation — the pattern of what people consistently say about you and come to you for\n\nYour natural wiring — named specifically enough to point to it\n\nWhen someone in an interview asks why you would be good at this role, you are not just saying you would be good at it. You are pointing to a body of evidence that says so. That is a completely different conversation from the one most candidates have.\n\nThis is also why so many people feel like they are bragging when they talk about themselves in an interview. They are asserting without evidence, and they know it. Assertion without evidence feels hollow, so it sounds hollow. Pointing to real evidence is just the truth, and truth spoken with specificity has a very different quality than a claim spoken into the air.\n\nA big part of the search process is not losing faith in yourself. When the offers have not come and the timeline has stretched beyond what you planned, the natural conclusion is that something must be wrong with you. You are not the problem. Getting the message right, directing it at the right companies, generating enough activity: these are the variables. But you need the self-belief to keep going while those variables sort themselves out. The convictions you build here are what that self-belief rests on when everything else feels uncertain.\n\nThink about a political candidate who knows her three core platform positions cold. No matter what question comes at her, she finds her way back to one of those three things. She is not guessing. She is not performing. She is anchored. There is a composure that comes from that kind of groundedness, a poised quality that people respond to even when they cannot quite name what it is. That is what you want in an interview: a place to stand, a set of things you know to be true about yourself that you can return to no matter where the conversation goes.\n\nContagious\n\nThe fourth C is not something you do. It is something that happens when the first three are in place.\n\nWhen you have done the work, when you know your convictions, when you have the clarity that comes from them, when you have built an evidence-based belief in your ability to deliver, something shifts in how you show up:\n\nThere is more conviction in your voice\n\nYour sentences do not run out of gas\n\nYou stop hedging\n\nThere is a composure to you that people feel before they can articulate it\n\nAnd the person across from you starts to feel it too.\n\nHere is the thing to understand about interviewing from the other side of the table: they want to hire somebody. They are trying to say yes to somebody. They have been through the process of identifying the need, writing the job description, reviewing resumes, and scheduling interviews. Now they are sitting across from you hoping that you are going to be the one so they can stop doing all of that.\n\nWhen you are convicted about what you bring to the table, you make it easy for them to say yes. You remove the doubt. You give them something solid to point to when they go back to their team and say: this is our person.\n\nWhen candidates do not believe what they are saying, the tells are everywhere:\n\nThe sentence that trails off without finding a period.\n\nThe answer that circles back on itself because something in the speaker knows it did not quite land.\n\nThe yeah and yeah at the end of a thought that had nowhere to go.\n\nInterviewers feel all of this, even when they cannot name it. They walk away unsure.\n\nAnd unsure does not get the offer.\n\nWhen you believe, you make me believe. That is the whole thing. That is what Contagious means. Not manufactured enthusiasm. Not performed energy. The real thing, built on a real foundation, that spreads to the person across from you because they can feel the difference.\n\nThe Sequence Matters\n\nConvictions lead to Clarity. Clarity leads to Confidence. Confidence is Contagious.\n\nThat sequence matters because it has to go in order. You cannot manufacture confidence without the convictions underneath it. And you cannot be contagious without the confidence underneath that. People can feel when the foundation is not there, even if they cannot name exactly what is missing.\n\nThe reason people often skip this work is that it takes time and it feels less urgent than updating the resume or applying to job postings. There are things that feel like progress you can be doing right now, and sitting with a blank page asking yourself what you would be fired over does not feel like one of them.\n\nBut the candidates who do this work first are the ones who show up to interviews with something the others do not have: a place to stand. A set of convictions that inform everything they say, that make their answers feel real because they are real, that make the interviewer lean forward instead of check out.\n\nThat is the competitive advantage that no resume formatting tip or interview hack can replicate. It comes from the inside. And it starts right here.\n\nReflection\n\nWrite your answers right now, before reading further: what are you looking for, and why you? Do not edit. Just write. What do you notice?\n\nWhat would you be willing to be fired over? Take ten minutes and write down three things. These are the beginning of your values.\n\nWhat are you naturally curious about, the topics, problems, or people groups you find yourself drawn to without anyone prompting you? How has that curiosity shown up across your career?\n\nWhat do people come to you for? What have you been told repeatedly in reviews, in passing, in the way colleagues have described you to others? That is your reputation speaking. Write it down.\n\nHave you taken the Affintus assessment or CliftonStrengths? If not, which will you do this week, and when specifically will you do it?\n\nIf you know your top strengths: what is the balcony of your strongest one? What is the basement? How would you answer a greatest weakness question using that honestly?\n\nHow clear are you right now on what you are looking for, on a scale of one to ten? What would move that number up two points, and what is one action you could take today to start moving it?\n\nLesson 4 — Bake a Cake and the Cherry on Top\n\nYou have done the foundational work. You know your convictions. You have clarity on what you are looking for and why. You have the evidence-based self-belief that becomes confidence in a room. Now comes the question that all of that work is preparing you to answer: how do you actually show up in a conversation?\n\nBecause having a strong background and being able to communicate it effectively are two different skills, and the gap between them is where searches often quietly stall. I work with people all the time who have impressive careers, real accomplishments, and interesting combinations of experience, and yet they walk into a networking conversation or an interview and present themselves like a document. Accurate. Well-organized. Completely forgettable. When I try to understand what happened, it almost always comes down to the same thing: they made a false choice without realizing they were making one.\n\nWhen someone has a varied background, the instinct is to pick one thing to lead with. Should it be the most recent role? The one they have held the longest? The thing they are most passionate about? The area that seems most marketable right now? Each of those instincts feels reasonable. But that framing forces you into a corner, and the corner undersells everything you actually bring to the table. You have reduced yourself to one ingredient when what the market needs is the whole cake.\n\nBake a Cake\n\nThink about what it actually takes to make a cake. You need eggs, flour, butter, and sugar. Each of those is a real ingredient with real properties, but none of them is a cake on its own. Flour by itself is just powder. Eggs alone do not get you anywhere interesting. The cake only exists when you combine the right ingredients in the right proportions, mix them together with some intention, and apply heat. And what comes out of the oven is something none of those individual ingredients could have produced by themselves.\n\nYour professional value proposition works exactly the same way. You have functional expertise. You have industry experience. You have natural wiring, the qualities that show up in how you work regardless of the context or the company or the role. You have a documented track record of specific accomplishments. You have passions and interests that connect, often more directly than you realize, to why you do the work you do and how you do it well. Each of those is an ingredient. The mistake people often make is presenting just one of them and calling it a cake.\n\nWhen you blend them together and synthesize your experience, your skills, your natural strengths, and your curiosity into a coherent, integrated story, something shifts in how people respond to you. At best, you become the unicorn: a combination of qualities and experiences that the company did not know existed until you walked through the door. At minimum, you become a distinctly differentiated candidate in a field where most people are presenting the same ingredients separately and wondering why nobody is reaching out. The goal is to take your various experiences and attributes and think creatively about how to blend them into a value proposition that is specifically and recognizably yours, one that answers not just what you have done, but who you are and why that particular combination of things makes you the right fit for what you are pursuing next.\n\nUsing AI to Bake the Cake\n\nThe good news is that you do not have to figure out the blending on your own. This is one of the most practical use cases I have found for AI tools, and it works remarkably well.\n\nTake everything you developed in the Convictions work from the previous lesson and put it into an AI tool like Claude or ChatGPT. Your core values, your why, your track record of accomplishments, your reputation as others have described it, and your natural wiring as revealed by whatever assessments you have completed. Then ask it to give you five different versions of your value proposition. Not five versions of your resume summary. Five different ways of synthesizing and expressing who you are and what you bring to the table.\n\nWhat you will find is that AI is quite good at seeing beyond the individual ingredients. It will notice patterns across your background that you have been too close to see yourself, draw connections between your experience and your wiring that you may have never explicitly made, and surface combinations that are more interesting than any single attribute on its own. Some of the five versions it produces will not resonate. But one or two of them will stop you mid-read and make you think: yes, that is actually it. Use those as the starting point for your Tell Me About Yourself (TMAY) and your broader positioning.\n\nThere is a second thing this exercise does that is equally valuable. Because AI can see the synthesis of everything you have put in front of it, it can also help you think about where to take your search. Ask it: given this profile, what kinds of roles am I best suited for and most uniquely qualified for? The answer will often surface opportunities you had not considered, reveal adjacent spaces where your particular combination of experience and wiring is rare, and give you language for pursuing things that might have felt like a reach when you were looking at any single part of your background in isolation. When you see the whole cake, the search strategy changes. You are no longer leading with the most recent job title and hoping for the best. You are leading with a synthesized story that a specific set of companies and roles will find compelling.\n\nThe Cherry on Top — Tell Me About Yourself (TMAY)\n\nThe work you just did with AI does not stop at the value proposition. Once you have a version or two that resonates, that synthesized story becomes the raw material for the most important sixty seconds of any job search conversation: your answer to Tell Me About Yourself (TMAY). You are not starting from scratch. You are taking the integrated picture that the AI helped you see and finding the human, personal entry point that makes it land as a story rather than a summary. That is what the cherry on top is about.\n\nPeople dread TMAY because it feels open-ended to the point of uselessness. Do you start with where you grew up? When you graduated? Do you summarize your entire career and hope they are still awake when you finish? The vagueness is actually deliberate. How you answer it tells the interviewer whether you know your own story, whether you can communicate it clearly, and whether you are a three-dimensional human being or a walking resume.\n\nBefore I give you the formula, I want to share an analogy that captures exactly what you are trying to do here. Think about house hunting. You visit thirty, forty houses. They all have roughly the right square footage, the right number of bedrooms, the right number of bathrooms. A few weeks later your partner asks: do you remember that house with three bedrooms and two and a half baths? You have no idea which one they mean. You looked at forty houses with three bedrooms and two and a half baths. But then they say: you remember, the one that smelled like Chinese food. Or the one with the huge oak tree in the backyard. And you know immediately, precisely, which house they mean.\n\nThe personal element in your TMAY is the oak tree. It is what makes you the house they remember when all the square footage starts to blur together. And it cannot be random. The personal detail has to connect, through a clear and logical arc, to your career and to what you are looking for next. That throughline is what makes it land as a story rather than a memorable footnote.\n\nThe formula has three parts.\n\nSomething about me personally. Start here, before the career, before the function, before the resume. They are hiring a human being, and the personal element is what makes you memorable and helps them connect with you before they have evaluated a single qualification. Think about what has always lit you up, what you do when nobody is telling you to, what has shaped how you think and how you work even if you have never explicitly connected it to your professional life. The AI work you just did may have surfaced some of this already.\n\nHow that has played out in my career. Now build the arc. The personal quality you just shared, the curiosity it reveals, the way of thinking it reflects, the discipline it required, connect it to the work you have actually done. This is where the ingredients blend into something coherent. The interviewer should be able to follow the logic: that quality led naturally to this kind of work, which explains why you have the specific experience and accomplishments you do. The story should feel inevitable in retrospect, as though the career makes complete sense given who you are.\n\nTherefore, what I am looking for is. Close it with specificity. Tell them exactly why you are in this conversation, not in a vague sense, but in a way that makes clear you have thought carefully about the fit between who you are and what they need. This is the part that makes everything actionable. It says: I know what I bring, I understand what you need, and I can see where they connect.\n\nThree parts. Something personal, how that has played out in my career, therefore what I am looking for. Said well, it runs about sixty seconds and it is the most important sixty seconds of any job search conversation.\n\nWhat This Looks Like in Practice\n\nHere is my own version. I have been doing the New York Times crossword puzzle for over six hundred consecutive days, which is a little obsessive, but that is just how I am wired. What I love about it, whether it is a Sunday crossword or a complex market challenge, is that there is always a theme to uncover, always something going on beneath the surface. I like the strategy of finding the theme, and I like that you use the parts you already know to figure out the parts you do not. That problem-solving mindset, the combination of strategic thinking and learning by doing, has shaped my entire career in sales leadership. I have almost always been in the same situation: launching new products, new divisions, new geographies, working in spaces where we know there is a market opportunity but do not yet have a complete playbook for how to capture it. Therefore, what I am looking for is the opportunity to lead a team in exactly that kind of environment, far enough along that there is something real to build, but early enough that there is still a puzzle to solve.\n\nSixty seconds. The interviewer now knows something specific and memorable about me, they understand how that connects to my career arc, and they know precisely what kind of role I am after and why it fits how I am built. That is a complete picture.\n\nHere is one for a musician who became a financial analyst. Playing the cello from a young age taught me three things at such a deep level that they became almost instinctual: discipline, precision, and collaboration. You have to be excellent in your own role while simultaneously listening to everyone around you, because if you are not, the whole performance falls apart regardless of how good you are individually. Those same principles have defined my career in finance, where technical accuracy is non-negotiable and so is the ability to work across functions, translate financial insight into language that actually drives decisions, and bring the right people into alignment around a shared picture of the business. Therefore, what I am looking for is a role where I can continue using both of those dimensions together, the analytical precision and the cross-functional partnership, to drive outcomes that matter to the whole organization.\n\nNow the interviewer is not thinking about a financial analyst. They are thinking about a musician who became a financial analyst, and those are very different people to have a conversation with. If they play an instrument, a connection just opened. If they do not, they are almost certainly more engaged than they were with the previous seven candidates who led with their accounting certifications.\n\nIn both of these, the personal element is not decoration or a warm-up act. It is the load-bearing structure of the whole answer. It gives the interviewer a frame for everything that follows, makes the career arc feel coherent and intentional rather than accidental, and makes the candidate someone worth remembering at the end of a long day of interviews.\n\nThe Black and White Problem\n\nI want to spend a moment on something that comes up almost every time I work through this with someone, because it represents the most common stumbling block in the whole exercise.\n\nWhen I ask people to share something personal, they often default back to professional framing. They mention that they worked in multiple countries, or that they have led large teams, or that they have managed significant budgets. These things are real and worth knowing, but they are still black and white. They are resume content delivered verbally. What I am listening for is color.\n\nI was working through this formula with someone in a session who had a strong professional narrative. Data to insights, insights to action. Category management with quantifiable results, double-digit growth in a declining market, significant revenue added in existing and new categories. His version was accurate and well-organized. It was also, when I pressed him on it, a black and white photograph of a career. Technically correct, missing the thing that makes a photograph feel like a person rather than a record.\n\nWhen I pushed him to go further and move past the professional framing, he mentioned almost tentatively that he loves reading about the geopolitics of World War II. He offered it the way people offer personal information when they are not sure it is welcome, as though it might be too much. And that tentativeness is exactly what I want to address.\n\nThe reluctance to bring something personal into a professional conversation is nearly universal, and I understand it. Interviews feel high-stakes, and the natural instinct is to minimize risk by staying in safe, well-lit professional territory. But what actually happens when everyone plays it safe is that everyone sounds the same. All the candidates say the correct things about their functional expertise, and the interviewer walks away unable to remember which one was which. Forty houses with three bedrooms and two and a half baths.\n\nWhat feels like risk, bringing a real piece of yourself into the conversation, is what creates the differentiation that actually gets the offer. And the passion you think is irrelevant to the work usually connects more directly than you realize. A fascination with the geopolitics of World War II, with the way complex competing forces interact, the way smarter strategy can overcome a disadvantage on paper, the way you have to move multiple pieces simultaneously while reading what the other side is going to do next, that is not separate from the ability to read market dynamics and find category growth where others see only headwinds. It is the same mind working in a different context. The connection just needs to be surfaced and articulated.\n\nWhen you find that connection between who you are and what you do, the question “why do you want this job” becomes almost unnecessary. The answer is already evident.\n\nPerfect Practice Makes Perfect\n\nThere is something important to say about practice, because people often use that word in a way that points them in the wrong direction.\n\nPractice does not make perfect. Practice makes habits. If you rehearse the wrong version of your story, you become very good at telling it wrong, and that habit will be hard to break once you are in the room that matters. What you need is perfect practice, and that requires getting the content right before you work on the delivery.\n\nStart by writing it out. Work through the three-part formula on paper until you have something that reflects your actual story, your actual arc, your actual voice. This is the scripting phase and it is not optional. The script gives you the right material to work with. But the script is not the destination.\n\nOnce the content is right, say it out loud. Words that have never been spoken will not sound natural when they come out for the first time in a room where the stakes are real. The transition that looked smooth on paper can fall apart when you hear yourself try to make it. The moment where you realize you do not actually believe what you are saying, none of that shows up until you open your mouth. Use the community for this. Use an accountability partner. Use an AI tool in voice mode that can listen and respond. Anything that gets the words into the air in a low-stakes setting where you can hear what is working, adjust what is not, and gradually internalize the story well enough that it comes out naturally and conversationally, as though you are simply telling someone the truth about yourself.\n\nBecause you are.\n\nYou may find you have two or three versions of your TMAY, one that leads with a life experience, one that draws from what you learned about yourself through an assessment, one that leads with a passion or personal interest. The formula stays the same across all of them. What shifts is which ingredient you lead with, calibrated to what you know about the person across from you and what matters in that particular conversation.\n\nThe goal is to walk into any room, hear Tell Me About Yourself, and feel clarity where there used to be anxiety. You know who you are. You know your story. You have said it before, in settings where it was safe to stumble, and you have worked out the rough spots. Now you are just telling the truth.\n\nReflection\n\nWrite down your cake ingredients: your functional expertise, your industry experience, your natural wiring, your track record, your personal interests and passions, your life experiences that connect to how you think and work. Write the full list without editing. What is there that you have not been using?\n\nHave you put your Convictions inventory into an AI tool and asked for five versions of your value proposition? If not, do that before moving to the next lesson. Note which versions resonate and why.\n\nAsk the AI: given this profile, what kinds of roles am I best suited for and most uniquely qualified for? What did it surface that you had not considered?\n\nWrite your first draft of your TMAY using the three-part formula: something personal, how that has played out in your career, therefore what I am looking for. Do not edit it. Just write it.\n\nNow say it out loud. Where does it feel forced? Where does it not sound like you? What needs to change?\n\nThink about the house hunting analogy. If someone described you after your last interview or networking conversation, would they be describing the square footage, or the oak tree?\n\nWhen is your next opportunity to practice your TMAY in a low-stakes setting? Name a specific time and place before you close this book.\n\nLesson 5 — Your Resume: Adjectives Are Not Accomplishments\n\nBy the time you reach this lesson, you have done the most important work in the curriculum. You know your convictions. You have clarity on what you are looking for. You have synthesized your value proposition and built your Tell Me About Yourself story. Now we need to translate all of that into your core piece of career collateral: the resume.\n\nA word of caution before we get into any of it. Everyone has an opinion about resumes. Former colleagues, career coaches, well-meaning friends, articles you found at two in the morning, the person in your networking group who has redesigned theirs six times and is convinced they have finally cracked the code. What ends up happening to many people is that they incorporate a little of everyone’s advice and end up with what I can only describe as a crazy quilt, a patchwork of conflicting guidance where the person reading it cannot figure out what the plot is supposed to be. Sometimes the writer cannot either.\n\nThe antidote to that is to start with first principles. What is a resume actually for? Once you are clear on that, a lot of the noise falls away.\n\nThe Sole Purpose of a Resume\n\nLaszlo Bock, who served as head of People Operations at Google during its most formative years, put it plainly: the sole purpose of a resume is to get you past the first screen. That is its job. Not to get you the offer. Not to tell your whole story. Not to document every role you have ever held and every responsibility you have ever carried. Its one job is to get you the interview, to get you into the conversation, to get you to the next stage of the process where the real selling can happen.\n\nThis sounds simple, but the implications are significant. If the resume’s job is to get you the interview, then every decision about what to include and how to say it should be evaluated against that single standard. Does this help me get the conversation? If yes, keep it. If it is just noise, cut it.\n\nThere is a second and equally important thing the resume does. When it is built well, it functions as the discussion guide for the conversation you want to have. Your bullets are not just a record of what you did. They are engineered to generate the specific questions you want to answer, the questions that let you demonstrate your expertise, the questions that set up the STAR stories you have developed. When an interviewer reads a bullet and says tell me more about that, they have just handed you the floor. The resume made that happen. Build your bullets with that in mind.\n\nAdjectives Are Not Accomplishments\n\nThis is the section title I have carried through every version of Making Your Own Weather, and I am keeping it because it is the most common and most costly mistake I see on resumes at every level.\n\nRead this out loud: I am a strategic, creative problem solver who liaises between stakeholders to drive results.\n\nNow ask yourself: what do you actually know about this person? Nothing. Every word in that sentence is an adjective or a vague claim. Strategic. Creative. Results-oriented. Easy to claim, hard to prove. Every candidate in the pile has a version of that sentence. It communicates only that you have heard the language of corporate job postings and know how to echo it back.\n\nThe language of business is numbers. Financial statements are numbers. Board presentations are numbers. When companies make decisions, they reach for data. When hiring managers evaluate candidates, the thing that stops them is specificity, a concrete result they can evaluate, a real number that gives them a frame of reference for the scale of your contribution. That is what we are building toward.\n\nLaszlo Bock offers a formula I find enormously useful: the XYZ formula: I accomplished X as measured by Y by doing Z. Each of those three elements carries its own weight:\n\nX is the outcome\n\nY is the measure that makes the outcome real and verifiable\n\nZ is how you did it — and this is the element people often skip\n\nThe Z matters as much as the what, because it tells the interviewer that you own a process, that you bring a framework with you, that the result you produced at your last company is not a lucky artifact of that particular environment but something you can replicate somewhere else. The Z is what makes an accomplishment portable.\n\nSarah Johnston, an executive resume strategist at Briefcase Coach, frames this similarly with what she calls the RAS formula — Result, Action, Skills — emphasizing the same sequence: lead with what you achieved, back it up with what you did to achieve it, and let the skills implied by those actions speak for themselves. Two frameworks, same essential truth.\n\nLet me show you what the difference looks like in practice.\n\nBefore: “Liaised with different teams to improve communication and collaboration.” After: “Led collaboration across five teams, reducing miscommunications by 30% and cutting project timelines by two weeks through structured check-ins and clear documentation.”\n\nThe first tells me you attended meetings. The second tells me you identified a problem, built a process to address it, measured the improvement, and owned the result. Those are completely different candidates.\n\nBefore: “Responsible for managing the company’s social media accounts.” After: “Increased social media engagement by 45% and grew the follower base by 20,000 in six months by implementing a data-driven content strategy and A/B testing posting cadences.”\n\nThe first is a job description. The second is an accomplishment and a discussion guide. Any interviewer who sees that bullet and has a social media problem at their company is going to ask: tell me about that data-driven content strategy. And you get to show exactly what you know.\n\nBefore: “Led a team of 15 with $3M budget responsibility.” After: “Reduced operational costs by 12% ($360,000) leading a 15-person team by redesigning workflows and renegotiating vendor contracts.”\n\nNow they know the outcome, they can do the math, they understand the scale, and they have a question ready: how did you find the efficiency in the vendor contracts? What did the workflow redesign look like? You are in business.\n\nThere is also a short list of phrases that actively work against you and should be removed from your resume entirely:\n\n“Liaised with” — signals that you were in the middle of things without being responsible for outcomes, and reads as overhead\n\n“Responsible for managing” — a job description, not an achievement; as I have been known to say, people get fired for not doing their job description, so telling me you did yours proves nothing\n\n“Participated in meetings” — a red flag; it tells me you were in the room and nothing about what you contributed\n\nIf any of these phrases are on your resume right now, replace them today.\n\nThe Three Value Levers\n\nEvery meaningful accomplishment on your resume should map to one of three things:\n\nMake money — revenue generated, new accounts opened, market share gained, products launched, sales targets exceeded\n\nSave money — costs reduced, efficiencies found, processes streamlined, time compressed\n\nMitigate risk — succession gaps addressed, compliance risks caught, conflict of interest situations resolved, data security vulnerabilities closed\n\nIf a bullet does not connect to at least one of these, it is most likely a job description masquerading as an accomplishment. Mitigating risk is the one people most often overlook, but it is enormously valuable when you can articulate it. These are not soft contributions. They protect the organization from outcomes that could cost far more than any efficiency gain would save.\n\nRun every bullet on your resume through this filter. If none of the three fit, ask yourself whether the bullet belongs at all.\n\nWhat to Do When You Do Not Have the Numbers\n\nThis is the question I get most often, and it deserves a direct answer.\n\nMany people do not have perfect data for everything they worked on. Particularly in large organizations where your contribution was one part of a multi-team initiative, or in research and advisory roles where the downstream business impact happened after you handed off the work, the exact number may not be knowable. That does not mean you leave the bullet blank.\n\nHere are three paths forward:\n\nReach back to former colleagues. Former clients, vendors, or internal partners who were part of the project. Ask: do you remember that initiative we worked on together? What were the results? You will often find that someone on the project knows exactly how things turned out, and they will be glad you asked. This is valuable networking in addition to being valuable research.\n\nGive an honest range. If the result was somewhere between three and five million dollars, say between three and five million dollars. You are not going to be audited. What the interviewer needs is a frame of reference, some sense of whether this was a ten-thousand-dollar impact or a ten-million-dollar impact, because those are very different conversations. Leaving the bullet entirely without a number forces the reader to guess, move on, or worse, assume you do not understand how to connect your work to business impact.\n\nUse time if you cannot use money. If you cut the monthly financial close from nineteen days to nine days to four days, say that. The cost reduction is implied, the increased agility is evident, and the interviewer can draw their own conclusion about what that was worth. Time saved, efficiency gained, risk reduced. Any of these counts.\n\nWe are not looking for perfection. We are looking for specificity that gives the reader something to evaluate.\n\nAbove the Fold\n\nHiring managers are time-pressed, and the window of attention your resume gets on first pass is short. Research consistently puts it at seven to ten seconds before a decision is made to keep reading or move on. Everything that matters needs to land before they scroll.\n\nThink about what a Greatest Hits album does. The record label does not make you listen to every album an artist has ever recorded in chronological order to find the songs worth knowing. They pull the best material together and put it in one place. Your resume needs a Greatest Hits section near the very top, before you get into the job-by-job chronology: three to five of your most significant accomplishments that best demonstrate your value and most directly connect to the kind of role you are pursuing. This is what gets them to keep reading.\n\nTwo formatting principles that serve you here:\n\nWhite space is your ally. A dense wall of text feels like work to a reader whose brain is actively looking for shortcuts. Give them room to breathe.\n\nUse selective bolding. Think about the toothpaste aisle. The label does not list all the ingredients on the front in equal-sized text. It tells you the two or three things the company most wants you to know: whiter teeth, fresher breath, stronger enamel, in the most prominent type they can fit on the packaging. Your resume should work the same way. If you grew revenue by 122%, which translated to seven million dollars, that number should be bolded. The reader’s eye will find it, and it will slow them down in the best possible way.\n\nUse selective bolding sparingly. If everything is bolded, nothing is. The selective part is the whole point.\n\nGetting Past the Machines — ATS\n\nBefore your resume reaches a human being at most companies, it passes through an Applicant Tracking System (ATS). These systems are designed to parse, rank, and filter applications, and they do not read resumes the way humans do. They scan for keywords, process section titles, and can be confused by formatting choices that look perfectly reasonable to the human eye.\n\nThree practical rules for your ATS-friendly resume:\n\nUse standard section titles — Work Experience, Education, Skills — not creative alternatives that a system will not recognize\n\nAvoid tables, columns, graphics, and text boxes — these can scramble when parsed and cause keywords to be missed or misread entirely\n\nTranslate non-standard job titles — if you were a “Chief Evangelist” but the role was effectively VP of Sales, lead with VP of Sales and note the actual title in parentheses; meet the reader, human or machine, where they are\n\nThis leads to a piece of advice that Sarah Johnston at Briefcase Coach and many others in the resume field are emphatic about: maintain two versions of your resume.\n\nThe ATS version is clean, simple, single-column, plain formatting, optimized for parsability. It will look a little bland, and that is fine, because it is not primarily for human eyes. It is for the machine that decides whether a human sees it at all.\n\nThe designed version is what you hand someone in a room, share at a networking event, or send directly to a person you have already connected with. That version can have more thoughtful formatting, visual hierarchy, and a more distinctive presentation.\n\nFeed the beast what the beast needs, and save the polish for the humans.\n\nAlways save your resume as a PDF. A Word document that looks perfect on your screen can render entirely differently on someone else’s machine. A PDF preserves your formatting exactly as intended, every time.\n\nThe One Thing to Remember\n\nWhen you step back from all of it, the XYZ formula, the three value levers, the Greatest Hits section, the ATS rules, what you are really doing is building a bridge. The interviewer is sitting at a company with specific problems to solve and specific results to produce. They do not ultimately care what you did at your last company for its own sake. They care about whether what you did there is relevant to what they are trying to accomplish here. Your job is to build that bridge as clearly and specifically as possible, so they can see the connection without having to work for it.\n\nThe resume gets you into the room. The work of getting the bullets right, connecting your accomplishments to real value, and making the document a discussion guide rather than a job log is what determines which rooms start opening up.\n\nYour LinkedIn Profile — The Resume’s Close Relative\n\nIf the resume is your targeted, result-rich document designed to get you past a specific screen for a specific role, your LinkedIn profile is something different. It is your digital first impression for the world, more personal, more narrative, more alive. The mistake many people make is treating LinkedIn as a place to paste their resume online. It is not that. It is a living document of who you are as a professional, and it operates by its own rules.\n\nThe two documents draw from the same raw material, your convictions, your track record, your value proposition. But they express that material differently. A resume is a formal, tightly edited submission to a specific opportunity. Your LinkedIn profile is the version of you that a recruiter finds when searching for someone with your background, that a hiring manager reads the morning before your interview to form an impression of who they are about to meet, that a former colleague forwards to someone at a company you have been trying to reach. It is always on, always visible, and doing work on your behalf whether or not you are actively in search. That is worth taking seriously.\n\nComplete the profile. LinkedIn’s algorithm rewards complete profiles by surfacing them higher in search results. A profile missing sections, no About section, no photo, a sparse experience section, is not just less compelling to human readers. It is less visible in the first place. You cannot be found if you are not showing up. Fill out every major section before anything else. Even a basic entry is better than a blank.\n\nThe photo. A LinkedIn profile without a photo reads as either unserious or evasive, and recruiters will move past it. The photo does not need to be a professionally produced headshot, but it needs to be clear, current, and approachable. A good image from the last few years with a neutral or professional background is sufficient. The photo and the headline are the only two things visible before someone clicks on your profile. Both need to pull their weight.\n\nThe headline. This is the most important and most neglected field on LinkedIn. Research consistently shows that the vast majority of users have never changed their headline from the platform’s default, which simply populates your most recent job title. That is a significant missed opportunity, because the headline is the primary field LinkedIn’s search algorithm uses to surface profiles in recruiter searches, and it is the first thing a hiring manager reads before deciding whether to click through.\n\nYou have 220 characters. Use them intentionally. A strong headline does two things simultaneously: it includes the keywords that recruiters in your space are actually searching for, drawn directly from the job descriptions of roles you are targeting, and it communicates something about the value you bring. Think of it as the first line of your personal advertisement. Do not fill it with vague descriptors. “Results-oriented professional” and “strategic leader” appear on so many profiles they have become invisible, and nobody is searching those terms. Do not lead with “Open to Work” or “Seeking Opportunities” for the same reason. Be findable for what you actually do, and give whoever finds you a reason to keep reading.\n\nA useful structure: your primary function or title, one or two areas of specific expertise, and a brief value statement or notable result. Separate elements with a pipe character or dash for readability. The first sixty characters or so are the most critical because they are what appears in search results and comment threads, so lead with what matters most.\n\nThe About section. Research across the LinkedIn community consistently finds that the About section is read far more often than people assume, and that readers respond far more positively to profiles written in first person than third person. Write yours in first person. Think of it as your TMAY in written form, something personal that earns attention, a clear arc connecting who you are to what you have done, and a closing statement about what you are looking for and why.\n\nOnly the first three lines are visible before someone has to click “See more,” so those lines need to do the work of making them want to. Start with a hook: a specific result, a compelling statement about what drives your work, or a personal detail that connects naturally to your professional arc. Do not open with your name and job title because LinkedIn already shows those. Use the opening to make someone think: I want to know more about this person.\n\nResearch from Briefcase Coach’s polling of thousands of LinkedIn users found that 56% appreciate finding personal details or a human element in profiles, and that 65% have reached out to someone they did not previously know because of something they read on that person’s profile. The personal element is not decoration. It is what makes people act.\n\nKeywords throughout. LinkedIn functions as a search engine and indexes keywords across multiple sections: the headline, the About section, the experience descriptions, and the skills section. Pull the most common terms from the job descriptions of roles you are targeting and weave them throughout your profile naturally. The goal is a profile that ranks well in search and reads well to a person. Those two things are compatible when done thoughtfully, and incompatible when keywords are stuffed in at the expense of real language.\n\nThe experience section. The same discipline from the resume applies here. Lead with accomplishments, not responsibilities. The XYZ logic holds: what you achieved, how it was measured, how you did it. LinkedIn gives you more room than a resume bullet, so you can add context, but the accomplishment needs to lead.\n\nOne important caveat that applies here more acutely than on the resume: LinkedIn is public. Before you publish any specific result, dollar figure, or business outcome, consider carefully whether that information is proprietary to your former employer or covered by a nondisclosure agreement. When in doubt, express the accomplishment in percentage terms or relative language rather than absolute numbers, or describe the nature of the result without disclosing the underlying data. “Significantly reduced operational costs through workflow redesign” is less specific than the resume version, but it protects you and your former employer without erasing the accomplishment entirely. When uncertain, err on the side of discretion.\n\nThe Featured section. LinkedIn allows you to pin content, including posts, articles, links, and documents, directly below your About section where every visitor sees it. This is underused and worth attention. It is where you can showcase work that demonstrates your expertise, link to thought leadership you have written, or surface content that shows rather than tells. If you have posted on LinkedIn and something has generated strong engagement, pin it. It gives profile visitors something concrete to interact with beyond the text of your profile.\n\nRecommendations. These are the LinkedIn equivalent of the reputation component from your convictions work in Lesson 3, third-party validation that did not come from you, which makes it inherently more credible than anything you say about yourself. A few well-written recommendations from people who can speak specifically to how you do your work carry real weight. Ask for them, and when you ask, give the person context about what you hope they will address. A specific recommendation pointing to a concrete project or outcome is worth far more than a warm but generic one.\n\nYour custom URL. LinkedIn assigns a string of numbers as your default profile URL. Change it to something clean, your name or a close variation. Put it on your resume, in your email signature, and wherever else you share professional contact information. It is a small thing that costs nothing and signals that you are paying attention to how you show up.\n\nThe two documents as a team. Your resume and your LinkedIn profile should reinforce each other. A recruiter who sees your resume will almost certainly look up your LinkedIn profile before deciding whether to call you. A hiring manager who finds you on LinkedIn will often pull your resume next. The two need to be consistent: same accomplishments, same story, same arc, expressed in voices appropriate to each format. The resume is formal and targeted. The profile is personal and always on. Both are doing your marketing. Make sure they are telling the same story.\n\nFor additional guidance on building a strong LinkedIn profile, Sarah Johnston at Briefcase Coach has compiled a body of free resources grounded in research across thousands of LinkedIn users. Her site is briefcasecoach.com.\n\nReflection\n\nPull out your resume right now and read every bullet through the XYZ lens. Does each one state what you accomplished, how it was measured, and how you did it? Mark the ones that are missing any of those three elements.\n\nRun every bullet through the three value levers. Does each one connect to making money, saving money, or mitigating risk? If not, does it belong on the resume at all?\n\nDo you have a Greatest Hits section near the top, above the fold? If not, what are the three to five accomplishments that most deserve to be there?\n\nAre there bullets where you do not have the numbers? For each one, identify one person you could reach out to this week who might know how those projects ended up.\n\nHow is your resume formatted? Is there an ATS-friendly plain version, and a more designed version for human readers?\n\nRead your professional summary or headline. Is there a single adjective in it that is not backed up by a specific accomplishment somewhere in the document? If so, replace it with something real.\n\nLook at your LinkedIn headline. Does it contain the keywords a recruiter in your space would actually search for? If you typed your target job title into LinkedIn search right now, would your profile appear?\n\nRead your LinkedIn About section out loud. Is it written in first person? Does it open with something that earns the click? Does it connect who you are to what you do and what you are looking for next?\n\nBefore you post any accomplishment publicly on LinkedIn, have you considered whether it is proprietary or covered by an NDA?\n\nPART THREE\n\nOutreach\n\nNow you buy media\n\n—\n\nLesson 6 — Networking: The Most Powerful Question\n\nEverything you have done up to this point has been preparation: the convictions work, the clarity, the synthesized value proposition, your TMAY, the resume. Rigorous, necessary, high-value preparation. Now we put it to work. Networking is where that preparation meets the world.\n\nSometimes we have to slow down to hurry up.\n\nFor Type A people, and there are a lot of you in this group, the preparation phase can feel deeply uncomfortable. You are wired for action, and action means being in real conversations with real people about real opportunities. The impulse to get out there before everything is ready is understandable, and it is also one of the most expensive mistakes you can make. You only get one first impression with each person in your network. Getting the plane on course first is far more important than flying two hundred miles an hour in the wrong direction. If you have done the work in the lessons that came before this one, you are ready. Now let us go.\n\nWhy People Struggle with Networking\n\nI want to spend a moment on why networking makes so many people uncomfortable, because the discomfort is real and understanding it is part of solving it. Many people who struggle with it fall into one of four camps:\n\nIt feels like using people, showing up with your hand out and asking for something without offering anything in return.\n\nIt feels like bragging, talking yourself up in a professional context runs counter to how many of us were raised.\n\nThey have no idea what they are supposed to do once they are in the conversation, and that uncertainty makes the whole thing feel vague and awkward.\n\nIt turns transactional very quickly. People go in looking for what I call red meat: do you know of any openings for me? That question turns a networking conversation transactional in about ten seconds, and the other person feels it immediately.\n\nEach of these is worth naming because each one has a specific antidote. By the end of this lesson I hope you will see networking not as something you endure but as something worth enjoying.\n\nThe Power of Weak Ties\n\nHere is something that is counterintuitive, and I say that because it was counterintuitive to me too.\n\nIn 1973, a sociologist named Mark Granovetter published research called The Strength of Weak Ties. The finding was striking: you are statistically much more likely to find your next job through people you do not know well, or do not know yet, than through your closest friends and family. LinkedIn has since analyzed data from hundreds of millions of professional connections and confirmed the same basic finding.\n\nThe natural instinct when you start a search is to go to the people who know you best. The people you trust most, who trust you most, who care the most about seeing you land well. That instinct makes complete sense. And the data says it is not where your next job is most likely to come from.\n\nThe reason, once you see it, is simple. Your close circle is traveling in the same information circles you are. They read the same industry news, attend the same events, and are connected to many of the same people. When you stay inside that orbit, you keep hearing about the same things. When you step outside it, you start to find things that would never naturally cross your path.\n\nWeak ties, the acquaintances you have not spoken to in years, the former colleagues who moved into different industries, the people you met once at a conference and connected with on LinkedIn, are moving in different orbits. They know people you do not know. They hear about opportunities in spaces you are not plugged into. Every conversation you have with someone outside your immediate circle expands the reach of who knows what you are looking for, and that reach is where the next opportunity is most likely to emerge.\n\nIf you feel like you have burned through your network and are recycling the same small group of names, the answer is not to dig deeper into the same pool. It is to grow the network. That is what this lesson is about.\n\nThe Most Powerful Question\n\nThe very first article I wrote on LinkedIn was called The Most Powerful Question You Can Ask. The question itself is simple, and when you understand what it actually does in a networking conversation, it changes the whole experience.\n\nHow can I be of help to you, personally or professionally?\n\nThe first thing I want to say about this question is that it is not a script. It is an attitude. You are going into the conversation with curiosity about the other person, a real interest in what they are working on, what they are trying to figure out, what they might need. You are entering not with your hand out but with your hand up, volunteering to help. That shift in posture changes everything about how the conversation feels, to you and to them.\n\nThe personally or professionally part matters more than it might seem. There will be people in your network where you cannot imagine how you could help them professionally. They are already the CFO of a major company, or they have moved into a field entirely different from yours. But they have a personal life. They have things going on outside of work. If you take the time to learn something about them as a human being, which is what the opening minutes of any good meeting are really for, you may find a way to offer something you never would have anticipated.\n\nThis question is also what transforms a networking conversation from a transaction into something more like an actual conversation. There is a dynamic that can take over in a job search where every meeting starts to feel a little like donor and recipient, where you are the one asking and the other person is the one deciding how much to give. The most powerful question breaks that dynamic. It says: I see you as an equal, I value what you know and what you are working on, and I am here for both of us. Stephen Covey wrote about this principle as seek first to understand, then to be understood. The networking version is seek first to help, and help will come. Sowing and reaping is a real thing. Show up to help consistently enough, and the natural course of events is that you will receive it in return.\n\nThere is also a practical dimension worth naming. When you are in a search and you set up a networking meeting, people generally know what is going on. There is no big secret. What they do not necessarily expect is that you are also trying to help them. That makes you differentiated in a way that is hard to manufacture and easy to remember.\n\nKevin at Starbucks\n\nI want to tell you a story that gets at something I think matters as much as any tactical advice in this lesson.\n\nA number of years ago, someone suggested that a man I will call Kevin reach out to me. Bob might be able to help you, they told him. So Kevin and I arranged to meet at a Starbucks.\n\nThe moment Kevin sat down, his body language said everything. He was backing away from me before we had even ordered. He was apologizing for wasting my valuable time. He was making himself small in every way a person can make themselves small in a professional setting. I finally said: Kevin, stop. I want to be here.\n\nBut what struck me was not the awkwardness of the moment. It was what the awkwardness revealed. An extended job search had done real damage to his sense of his own value. He had been in the market long enough that the silence had started to feel like a verdict. He could not see what he was bringing to the table in that Starbucks, the knowledge I did not have, the experiences I had not had, the connections he might know that I did not. He could not see that there might be something he could do for me. He only saw the gap between where he was and where he wanted to be, and that gap had convinced him he had nothing to offer.\n\nI share this because I suspect it resonates with more than a few people reading this. A long search has a way of eroding the very confidence you need most. But here is what I want you to hold onto: you have assets. You have knowledge, relationships, experience, and perspective that matter to the people you sit across from. A networking conversation is an exchange, not a charity transaction. Walk in like it.\n\nWho to Contact\n\nMany people approach their networking list by going to the most senior people they know, or simply the people they are most comfortable with. Both of those instincts are understandable, and both leave a lot on the table. Here is how I think about prioritizing the list instead.\n\nLikelihood to help. Start with the people who are known to be generous, who have helped you or others before, who you sense will show up for you because that is just who they are. If someone in your network has been through a job search themselves and come out the other side, they are often among the most empathetic and useful conversations you can have. They know the terrain.\n\nProximity to desired opportunities. If you are pursuing specific roles or companies, think about who in your network has some connection to that world. They know the industry, they know the players, they may even know people at the companies you are targeting. When you are networking you are asking for directions, and it helps to talk to people who know the neighborhood.\n\nSalespeople. Put them high on the list. Salespeople will help you, and I say this with confidence. They are natural networkers. They understand the value of relationships, they tend to be optimistic and generous with introductions, and they simply know a lot of people. Whatever their reasons, they show up. Seek them out.\n\nFormer colleagues you have not spoken to in years. This one stops a lot of people cold. It feels strange to reach out to someone you have not talked to in seven years, or seventeen. Like you need a better reason than just being in a search.\n\nHere is the flip I encourage people to try. If that person called you today, how happy would you be to hear from them? Pretty happy, right? She was great. I really liked working with her. Of course I would take her call. She is probably thinking the exact same thing about you. The weirdness lasts about half a second, and then you are two people who used to work together catching up on what has happened since.\n\nWhat I find is that people often make this decision for the other person before giving them a chance. She is too busy. It has been too long. She has moved into a different field. These are stories we tell ourselves, and they are usually wrong. Stop making decisions for people. Give them the opportunity to help. People like to give, and most of the time they are glad you asked.\n\nOne practical note: download your LinkedIn connections. If you have been on the platform for any length of time, you likely have a thousand or more contacts. The chances are good that you have had meaningful contact with fewer than half of them, which means you have hundreds of warm contacts with a natural reason to hear from you. Many of them are exactly the kind of weak ties the research says are most likely to lead somewhere. Start there.\n\nBefore the Meeting\n\nA networking conversation is only as good as the preparation that goes into it. Here is what that looks like.\n\nResearch the person before you meet. Look at their LinkedIn. Read anything they have written or spoken on publicly. Note any shared connections, any common ground. Five minutes of preparation communicates more care than people often show, and it sets up the entire conversation differently.\n\nRemember who introduced you, and say so. When you get on the call, acknowledge the connection. When I ask people how they found me and they cannot remember, it tells me something about how they think about relationships. When someone says Rob introduced us, and I appreciate that, it tells me this is a person who pays attention and values the people in their network. It is a small thing that is not actually small.\n\nHave your TMAY ready. You are asking for directions. You need to know where you want to go. If the other person asks what you are looking for and the answer is I am open to a lot of different things, you have made it hard for them to help you. Know your story, know your target, and be able to say both clearly.\n\nBring a target company list. There is a concept in market research called aided versus unaided awareness. If I ask you to name every beer brand you can think of in fifteen seconds, you will rattle off a handful and then start to slow down. If I show you a list of fifty brands, you will recognize almost all of them immediately. Your brain needed the prompt. The same thing happens when you bring a list of target companies to a networking conversation. Instead of putting all the cognitive load on the other person to generate ideas from scratch, you give them something to react to. Oh, if you are interested in those companies, what about this one? I actually know someone there. That list fires their imagination in a way that an open-ended question simply cannot, and it multiplies the usefulness of every conversation you have.\n\nThe Meeting\n\nA good networking conversation has a natural shape to it, and once you have been through a few of them you will start to feel it.\n\nStart with Rock’s Fab Five. My friend Rock Robinson is one of the best natural relationship builders I have ever known, and he shared with me a simple framework for the opening minutes of any conversation that I have used ever since. The five areas are:\n\nWhere were you born and raised?\n\nWhere did you go to school?\n\nTell me about your family.\n\nWalk me through your career.\n\nWhat are you passionate about outside of work?\n\nThese are not idle small talk. They are active information gathering, and they do something important: they surface the points of human connection that make a networking conversation feel like a conversation between two people rather than a transaction between a job seeker and a contact. When you find out that the person you are talking to grew up in the same city as your brother, or went to your school, or has kids the same age as yours, or is passionate about something that someone in your network could help with, the whole dynamic shifts. You are no longer two strangers on a call. You are two people with something real in common, and that is where relationships actually start.\n\nThe Fab Five also opens the door to the most important thing you can do in a networking conversation, which is look for ways to help. When you know something about where someone is from, what they care about, what they are working on, and what they love outside of work, the opportunities to offer something worth giving become much more visible. Pay attention. People are often surprised that someone they just met was listening closely enough to find a way to help them, and that surprise is itself a form of differentiation that most candidates never think about.\n\nTell your story. This is your TMAY moment. Be clear about where you have been, why you are where you are, and what you are looking for next. The person across from you wants to help. Give them what they need to do that.\n\nAsk the most powerful question. How can I be of help to you, personally or professionally? Ask it sincerely and then listen. People will often say they cannot think of anything right now but appreciate you asking. That is fine. The fact that you asked changes how they see you. Occasionally they will tell you something real, and when they do, take it seriously and follow through on it.\n\nFor recruiters, add one more question. Before you wrap up: are there any roles you are working on right now that are particularly hard to fill? Is there anyone in my network you think I might be able to connect you with? Nobody asks recruiters this question. It surprises them, and it helps them. If you happen to know someone who fits what they are struggling to find, you have just become someone worth staying in touch with.\n\nAsk who else you should speak with. This is the real goal of networking, not to extract a job lead from every conversation but to grow the network itself. Make it an open-ended question: based on what you know about what I am looking for, who else would you suggest I speak with?\n\nThen stop talking.\n\nThat pause is called Golden Silence. Seven seconds is about when people start to get uncomfortable and fill the void. Do not fill it. Let them think. The name that comes out of that silence is often the most valuable thing that comes out of the entire meeting.\n\nAfter the Meeting\n\nThe meeting is not over when the call ends, and what you do next is where many people quietly drop the ball.\n\nThank the person you just met. Do it the same day, while the conversation is fresh. Be specific about something they said or something you took away. A generic thank you is close to no thank you. A specific one says you were paying attention and that their time mattered.\n\nThank the introducer separately. Tell them who you met, what you talked about, and why you appreciated being connected. When I receive a note like that, I will help that person again without hesitation, because they have shown me they value relationships and not just the immediate transaction. When someone never follows up, I notice that too.\n\nOffer to write the introduction copy. If someone offered to introduce you to a third person, offer to write the copy for them: would it be helpful if I sent you a couple of sentences about who I am and what I am looking for, so you can just paste it in? Write it in the third person so they can use it directly. This does two things. It keeps you in control of your own message. And it removes the friction that causes well-intentioned introductions to quietly never happen. A lot of people mean to follow through on a commitment like this and never quite get there, not because they do not care but because it feels like one more thing. You can solve that problem for them before it starts.\n\nKeep any commitments you made. If you said you would send an article, send it. If you said you would introduce them to someone, do it. Your credibility as a networker is built one kept commitment at a time.\n\nStaying Organized\n\nWhen networking is working well, it multiplies quickly. One conversation leads to several introductions, which lead to several more conversations. That is a good problem to have, and it requires a simple system to manage.\n\nI will be direct with you: I originally built a CRM tool into Career Club specifically for this purpose. What I found was that almost everyone defaulted to a simple spreadsheet, because it was the tool they already knew how to use. The best system is the one you will actually use. Think of it like exercise: the best workout is the one you actually do.\n\nFor many people a spreadsheet is all you need. Date, person, title, company, who introduced you, what you committed to do next. Update it immediately after every conversation while the details are fresh, and you will thank yourself every single week. What will stress you out most in an active networking phase is not the volume of conversations. It is remembering next week something you should have done last week.\n\nA Book Worth Reading\n\nThe 20-Minute Networking Meeting by Nathan Perez is the most useful thing I have found on the craft of the networking conversation. It takes everything in this lesson and goes deeper on the discipline and structure of how to do it well. I interviewed Nathan on my podcast a few years ago, and that conversation is still available on most podcast platforms if you want a preview. But if you have the time, read the book.\n\nReflection\n\nThink about your current networking list. Are you going to the people you are most comfortable with, or the people most likely to help? Who are the three most generous people in your network, and have you reached out to them?\n\nHave you downloaded your LinkedIn connections? If not, do it this week. Identify ten people you have not spoken to in over a year who might be a valuable conversation, and reach out to at least three of them before the next lesson.\n\nThe next networking conversation you set up, prepare a target company list in advance and bring it. Notice what happens when you share it.\n\nThink about the Kevin at Starbucks story. On a scale of one to ten, how much do you actually believe right now that you have something to offer the people you are networking with? If that number is below seven, what would it take to move it up?\n\nAfter your next networking conversation, write the thank you note the same day. Make it specific. If someone offered to make an introduction, offer to write the copy for them.\n\nWhat is your current system for tracking networking activity? If you do not have one, set up a simple spreadsheet before your next conversation and use it.\n\nLesson 7 — Direct Outreach: Making Your Own Weather\n\nYou have built the brand. You have the message. Networking is expanding the reach of who knows what you are looking for. Now it is time to talk about pipeline.\n\nThink of yourself as a salesperson. You have been trained in your product. That is everything we have done in the lessons up to this point. You know your value proposition. You know how to talk about it. Now you need to hit your quota. And as we said at the very beginning of this course: your quota is exactly one. You do not need to convince the whole market. You need one company to say yes.\n\nBut to hit that quota in a reasonable amount of time, you need a rich pipeline of opportunities working simultaneously at different stages. Some of those opportunities will come from online applications. Some will come from recruiters. Some will come from networking leads. Each of those is a legitimate channel, and you should be working all of them.\n\nThere is a fourth channel that people rarely use at all. This is making your own weather.\n\nYou will remember from the Introduction Stephen Covey’s distinction between the circle of concern and the circle of control. The circle of concern contains everything you worry about but cannot directly affect. The circle of control contains what you can actually do something about right now. Let us apply it directly to how a job search pipeline is built.\n\nLook at how much job search activity maps onto those two circles. Job postings live in the circle of concern. You are waiting for someone else to decide there is a need and publish it. Recruiter relationships live there too, because you are waiting for them to find you, remember you, and match you to something. Online applications live there as well. You submit and then you wait, with no visibility into what happens next or whether anyone is looking at what you sent. In all of these, the next move belongs to someone else.\n\nDirect outreach lives entirely in the circle of control. You decide which companies to target. You do the research. You write the note. You send it. You follow up. Every element of this process is yours to initiate, and the next move is always in your hands. That shift is not just tactical. Over a long search, it is a psychological one. When you spend your days in the circle of concern, where outcomes are out of your hands and feedback is slow and often silent, you start to lose the sense of agency you need to keep going. Direct outreach gives that back.\n\nThe RFP Problem\n\nEvery salesperson knows that you cannot build a pipeline by waiting for Requests for Proposals. You have to go and create conversations with companies that may or may not know yet that they have a need for what you sell.\n\nA job posting is an RFP. Your resume is your RFP response. You submit it and then you hope and pray they call you back. You have no visibility into the process, no access to the people making the decision, no way to stand out from the pile.\n\nI sometimes ask people to imagine telling their sales manager that the reason their pipeline is empty is that they have not gotten enough RFPs in. That person would be fired on the spot. And yet that is exactly how job seekers often run their search.\n\nThree Reasons to Reach Out Without a Posting\n\nThere is a persistent fear underneath this approach: why would I reach out to a company if I do not know they have an opening? The answer is that the opening does not have to exist yet for you to be exactly the right person to reach out. There are three scenarios that are far more common than people realize.\n\nThe B-minus incumbent. They already have someone in that role. His name is Bob. He is not terrible. He is not amazing. He is a B-minus, and right now he is good enough because he is nobody’s biggest problem. Bob has that job until Stephanie shows up and proactively reaches out. And the hiring manager thinks: why am I putting up with Bob when I could have Stephanie?\n\nThe unarticulated need. The hiring manager knows she needs someone like you. She thinks about it on the drive to work. She thinks about it when something breaks. But she has not taken it to HR yet, has not gotten budget, has not asked anyone to write a job description. The need is real. It just exists only in her head. When you show up in her inbox, you are answering a question she had not yet figured out how to ask.\n\nThe open search with no winner. They have been interviewing for three months. Twelve people have come through and nobody has been quite right. Until you show up.\n\nIn all three cases, you are not applicant number 721 at the back of the line. You are a one-of-one.\n\nThe Outreach IS the Interview\n\nThere is something important underneath the tactical case for direct outreach that is easy to miss.\n\nWhen you reach out to a targeted company with a researched, personalized, thoughtful note, you are not just creating a job opportunity. You are demonstrating in real time, through your own behavior, that you are a proactive, self-starting, initiative-taking person. You are not claiming it on your resume. You are showing it. Some of the best salespeople I know, when asked in an interview why they should be hired, have answered simply: I got to you, didn’t I?\n\nRelevant and Differentiated\n\nBefore we get into the structure of the outreach, I want to talk about what makes it work, because structure alone is not enough.\n\nThink about a two-by-two matrix. One axis is relevance. The other is differentiation. Each quadrant tells a story.\n\nHigh relevance, low differentiation is a commodity. Think about gasoline. You need it. Every car needs it. But are all gasoline brands meaningfully different from one another? Not really. So you shop on price and convenience. If your outreach is relevant to what the company does but sounds like every other email in their inbox, you are relevant but not a priority.\n\nLow relevance, high differentiation is the box of chocolates someone sends to a hiring manager with a note that says, wouldn’t it be sweet to work with me? Different, but not in a way that helps you.\n\nLow relevance, low differentiation is the mass-apply approach. Five hundred applications, five hundred generic cover letters, five hundred black holes. There is no point being there.\n\nHigh relevance, high differentiation is the sweet spot. That is what we are building toward.\n\nAnd the secret sauce that makes a highly relevant, highly differentiated outreach land is timing. When you identify a signal that something has recently changed at a company, you have a reason to reach out that is both specific and timely. The signals to look for:\n\nA funding round closed\n\nAn acquisition completed\n\nA new geography opened\n\nA product launched\n\nA new category entered\n\nChange creates need. Need creates opportunity. When you find those signals and connect them to your value proposition, you are no longer a cold outreach. You are a well-timed conversation.\n\nThe Subject Line Comes First\n\nIt does not matter how good the email is if it does not get opened.\n\nThe subject line is the single most important element of the whole outreach, and people often treat it as an afterthought. The goal of a great subject line is simple: make their ego want to open it. Lead with their name, then give them a specific reason to be curious about what you found. Something that says, without saying it directly: I have been paying attention to you, and I have something worth your time.\n\nSome examples of what this looks like:\n\nJulie — Your talk at TechWorld\n\nJames — Your comments in the WSJ\n\nMelissa — Point 3 in your HBR article\n\nBrian — Colgate’s shelf opportunity at Walmart\n\nEach of these is specific enough to be intriguing and personal enough to feel like it was written for that person alone. The recipient does not yet know whether to agree with your observation, but they want to find out. That is all you need to get them to click.\n\nA word on channel. Because job seekers spend so much time on LinkedIn, they naturally assume that the people they are trying to reach are equally active there. That is frequently not the case. Unless you can see from someone’s posting activity that they are active on the platform, a LinkedIn InMail or personalized connection request may sit unread for days or disappear entirely. Everybody is on email. Use email as your primary channel. LinkedIn is a backup for people you can confirm are active there.\n\nOne more note on senior executives: the more senior the person, the more likely their calendar is managed by someone else. Offer to coordinate through their EA. Say it exactly that way: their EA. It signals immediately that you understand how senior people operate, and it gives the executive an easy way to say yes without adding a task to their own plate.\n\nThe Template — Three Paragraphs, Not a Form Letter\n\nDirect outreach works when it is human-voiced, specific, and structured. The goal is not a form letter, and it is not a three-hour work of art per company either. The template gives you a structure that lets you move with some efficiency while still sounding like a real person wrote it for a real person.\n\nAs you do a few of these, you will start to find your rhythm. Each one gets a little faster. But what you are never doing is blasting out the same email to five hundred people and hoping something sticks. This is the slow-down-to-hurry-up principle applied to outreach. Take the time to do this right, and you will get results that mass applying will never produce.\n\nParagraph one — start with them. This is where the signal you found becomes the hook. Reference something specific — the talk they gave, the article they wrote, the funding round they just closed, the product they just launched. Make it clear you were actually paying attention. This is not flattery. It is a real observation that demonstrates you understand what they are working on and why it matters.\n\nParagraph two — brief about me. I am not a complete stranger. A few sentences: who you are, what you do, and two or three specific accomplishments that connect to what they care about. This is where your XYZ bullets earn their keep.\n\nParagraph three — why there might be a fit. Connect their world to your world. Say why you think there could be something worth a conversation. The ask is simple: can we talk? Not: please consider me for a role. Just: can we find thirty minutes?\n\nThink about how a great salesperson approaches a first meeting. They do not send the full PowerPoint presentation with the first outreach. They earn the right to show it. Leave the resume out of the initial note. When they ask for it, that is the conversation starting, and the conversation is what you are after.\n\nWhat This Looks Like in Practice\n\nHere is a real example of this template in action, drawn from work with a Career Club member in market research. The subject line alone tells you this email is going to get opened.\n\nSubject: Susan — Your comments on the Bright Ideas podcast\n\nHi Susan,\n\nRecently I have been researching Trident, and I came across your comments on the Bright Ideas podcast last month. One insight you shared that particularly resonated with me was the assertion that marketing research will never get a seat at the table until it can tie research projects to real business results. My experience is that the key to making this transformation is driving a greater focus during the initial scoping of projects to identify exactly what actions you will take once the project is complete. Absent that, most research ends up in the “nice to know” file.\n\nMy career has been helping companies like Trident achieve exactly what you described. Some relevant accomplishments include:\n\nLed an insights team that achieved 17% share growth year over year, worth approximately $54M in incremental sales, by replacing a traditional attitudinal segmentation model with an actionable Need States methodology for digital ad targeting\n\nRe-engineered the research brief process, resulting in a 20% improvement in research turnaround by conducting the right research right the first time\n\nIdentified 39% advertising spend inefficiencies, resulting in a $17M redeployment from TV to more effective digital placements\n\nCan we find thirty minutes over the next two weeks to get acquainted and explore whether my skills are a good match for Trident? From there we will both likely know whether there is a basis for continuing the conversation. If we have not connected by the 13th, I will follow back up with you.\n\nWalk through it and notice what is happening at each step.\n\nThe subject line references something she actually said on a specific podcast. Her ego wants to know what you thought of it. She opens the email.\n\nParagraph one leads with her idea, not with an introduction. It demonstrates that you listened closely enough to have a reaction of your own. It also adds a real observation, the scoping point, that shows you are not just flattering her, you are engaging with her thinking. She is already reading differently than she reads the other emails in her inbox.\n\nParagraph two is brief and specific. Three XYZ bullets with real numbers, each one directly relevant to the problem she described in paragraph one. No adjectives. No claims. Evidence.\n\nParagraph three makes a small, low-stakes ask. Not a job application, just a conversation. And notice the last sentence: she has already committed to following up if they have not connected by the 13th. That sentence does two things. It signals that she is serious, and it gives Susan a gentle deadline that makes her more likely to respond rather than let it drift.\n\nThat is the whole template working together.\n\nWho to Contact\n\nNot HR. Not Talent Acquisition. The person who owns the problem you are solving. The functional leader who would be your direct manager, or their manager. The person who feels the gap you are there to fill.\n\nFinding their email address is not the obstacle it seems. The vast majority of professional email addresses follow one of two patterns: firstname.lastname@companydomain, or first initial and last name at company domain. That covers ninety-five percent of the universe. If neither works, Hunter.io will sort it out for you. Do not let the email address become the reason you do not start.\n\nBob’s Origin Story\n\nThis lesson takes its name from something that actually happened to me, and it is worth telling properly because it is the whole proof of concept.\n\nSeveral years ago I found myself in a business partnership that had stopped working. My partner held sixty percent of the equity; I held forty. Forty percent never outvotes sixty, and there were decisions being made that I could not live with. So Bob had to find something new.\n\nI did the only thing I knew how to do. I made a list of the top market research firms in the country, companies that had every reason to be interested in someone with my background. I found the CEO of each one. I went to their websites, their press releases, their industry coverage, looking for one specific piece of news or insight I could use as a hook. Something that said: I have been paying attention to what you are doing and I have something relevant to say about it. And then I sent a version of this email to each of them.\n\nMy phone rang off the hook.\n\nOne of the calls came from a talent acquisition person at a company whose CEO had personally asked him to follow up with me. He was a little puzzled. He said: honestly, we do not even have a sales function here, so I am not sure why she wanted me to call you. Then he paused and said something I was not expecting. He told me he had just left a firm called NPD Group six weeks prior. He said they were looking for someone to build out their consumer electronics practice. He thought I would be exactly right for it. And then he gave me the name, the direct phone number, and the email address of the hiring manager, and told me to use his name.\n\nI had a job offer in three weeks.\n\nNone of it happens if I do not develop my value proposition, build the target list, do the research, write the outreach, and follow up. Every step connects to the next. None of it happens, most of all, if I do not send the first email. You cannot control who responds, or what they know, or what unexpected connection is waiting on the other side of a conversation you have not yet started. **What you can control is whether you begin.\n\nJulie’s Story\n\nJulie was part of the Career Club community when she decided to try this approach. She was petrified, like many people reading this are right now.\n\nShe sent her version of this note to Cognitive Consulting. Not to the managing director, not to the functional head. She sent it to the general info inbox on the Contact Us page. Not ideal by any stretch. But whoever read that inbox thought it was compelling enough to forward up the chain.\n\nThey did not have a role for what Julie did. They created one for her.\n\nWhen she came back to the group to share what had happened, someone pointed out that it must have been easy for her since she came from a sales background. Julie said it took her six weeks to work up the nerve to send the first one. Six weeks. She said this was the opposite of her natural personality, that she had gotten very much out of her comfort zone to do it.\n\nAnd then it got easier.\n\nThe worst that can happen is nothing. You are already not working at that company. You cannot be rejected from a job that was never posted. People who receive a thoughtful, personalized, well-timed note like this will appreciate the initiative. And if by some chance someone finds it unwelcome, that probably tells you something useful about whether that is the right place for you anyway.\n\nUsing AI to Build the Territory\n\nWhen I first developed this approach, building the target company list meant hours of manual research. That has changed considerably.\n\nAI tools — Claude, ChatGPT, Gemini, Perplexity — can now help you build a target company list based on your value proposition, filter by geography, industry, size, or funding recency, surface relevant hooks from news and press releases, identify the right person to contact, and draft personalized versions of the template for each company. What used to take a full day can now take an hour.\n\nA useful example: ask the AI to find companies in your space and metro area that have raised significant funding recently. Companies that have recently raised are, by definition, growing, and growing companies are hiring across most functions. The AI will tell you what it found, why it made the list, and what recent news or announcements you could use as a hook in your outreach note. Then ask it to draft the email. Review it, make it sound like you, and send it.\n\nInformation is no longer the limiting factor. Creativity and execution are. The tools do the research. You bring the judgment about what matters, and the voice that makes it sound like a human being wrote it.\n\nFollow-Up Is Where It Falls Down\n\nThis is the most common reason people try this once and decide it does not work. They send the email. They hear nothing. They conclude the approach is flawed and they stop.\n\nWhen I ask those people about their follow-up, the conversation always goes the same way. What follow-up? I figured if they were interested they would have reached out. And that assumption is almost always wrong.\n\nBusy people get your email, find it interesting, and their phone rings. They go to a meeting. Something urgent comes up. They are in Europe all week. They did not reject you. They got distracted. Your follow-up is doing them a favor. For all you know, they were just about to have someone in talent acquisition reach out to you when a Slack message pulled them away and it slipped off the radar. That gentle nudge brings you back to the top of a crowded inbox.\n\nHere is when to send the follow-up: Friday afternoon, after 2:00 p.m. in the recipient’s time zone. People rarely have meetings late on a Friday afternoon. They are in a good mood. They are trying to tie up loose ends before the weekend. A friendly, light-touch note arriving at that moment tends to get a response in a way that a Tuesday morning follow-up simply does not.\n\nWhen you follow up, reply directly to your original email so the context is immediately visible below. The note itself should be brief and warm:\n\nHi Brian — just wanted to follow up on my note below. I genuinely hope we can find a few minutes to connect over the next week or two. Thanks, and have a great weekend!\n\nThat is it. The magic is in the timing and the warmth, not in making a second case for yourself. You are not trying to resell them on what a strong candidate you are. You are bumping yourself back up in their inbox in a light, friendly, human-voiced way. And your follow-up may actually be doing them a favor. There is a long list of reasons a response never came, and that gentle Friday nudge is often all it takes to get it.\n\nMaking Your Own Weather\n\nEvery other channel requires you to wait, and this one does not.\n\nWhen you send one of these notes and something comes back, a reply, a phone call, a message saying I am so glad you reached out, and what you feel in that moment is different from anything the application black hole ever gives you, because you made that happen. You put something in motion that would not have moved without you.\n\nAnd here is what tends to follow from that. The first response gives you the confidence to send a second outreach, which is easier to write because you already know it can work. One conversation leads to an introduction you did not see coming, which leads somewhere that has nothing to do with where you thought you were headed when you sent the first email. Proactive action produces results, and results encourage more proactive action. The cycle builds on itself in a way that reactive searching simply cannot replicate, because every step forward is something you initiated rather than something you waited for.\n\nThat is what it means to make your own weather. Not hoping the conditions improve, but doing fewer things with more intention, more research, and more relevance, and following up with warmth until something opens up. Do enough of that consistently, and you will have made your own sunshine.\n\nReflection\n\nHave you been waiting for postings to appear before you engage with target companies? What would it mean for your search to flip that dynamic?\n\nMake a list of ten companies you would want to work at even if they have nothing posted. That is your starting territory.\n\nFor the top three companies on that list, spend fifteen minutes looking for signals of recent change — a funding round, an acquisition, a new product, a new geography. Find one specific hook you could lead with in an outreach note.\n\nThink about the B-minus incumbent scenario. Is there a company where you know, based on what you have seen in the market, that they could be doing much better in your functional area? That is a company worth reaching out to.\n\nDraft your first subject line. Make it specific enough that the recipient would have no doubt it was written for them alone.\n\nWrite a draft of the first outreach. Three paragraphs. Start with them, not with you.\n\nWhat is your follow-up plan? Friday afternoon, after 2:00 p.m. in their time zone. Put it in your calendar before you send the first note.\n\nPART FOUR\n\nInterviewing\n\nEverything before this was preparation. This is game day.\n\n—\n\nLesson 9 — STAR: The Company Is Hiring Your Brain\n\nEverything that has come before this lesson, the attitude work, the community, the convictions and clarity, the resume, the networking, the direct outreach, has been preparation. All of it was designed to get you to one place. Game day is interviewing. This is when someone looks across a table or a screen and decides whether you are the person they have been searching for, and getting good at it matters more than almost anything else in the process.\n\nSo we are going to spend real time here. Not a checklist. Not a set of tips. A way of thinking about how to show up in an interview that will serve you across every conversation, every company, and every role you pursue from here.\n\nThe Resume Gets You the Interview. The Stories You Tell Will Get You the Job.\n\nYour resume did its job. It communicated enough about who you are and what you have done to earn you a seat at the table. That is all it was ever designed to do. What happens at the table is a completely different challenge, and it requires a completely different skill set.\n\nThe skill is storytelling, and not storytelling in the sense of being engaging or entertaining, though those things help. Storytelling in the sense of taking your real experience, structuring it so that the relevant parts are visible, and delivering it in a way that connects to what the person across from you is trying to figure out. That is the craft we are developing in this lesson.\n\nWhat the Company Is Actually Hiring\n\nEvery role that gets filled exists for one of three reasons: to help the company make money, save money, or mitigate risk. That is the full universe of why companies create positions and pay salaries. And when an interviewer is sitting across from you, they are doing a calculation, whether they have articulated it to themselves or not, that sounds something like this: can what this person has done, the way they think, the results they have produced, connect to the problems we are trying to solve?\n\nYour job in every interview is to narrow that gap as specifically and explicitly as you can. They do not ultimately care what you did at your last company for its own sake. They care about what it signals for what you will do at their company. The bridge between those two things is the story you tell, and how you tell it.\n\nAnd underneath all of that, here is the thing that most candidates miss: they are hiring your brain. Not your resume. Not your list of previous employers. Your brain. They want to understand how you approach problems, what you notice that other people overlook, what frameworks you bring to complexity, and why the choices you make are the choices you make. The candidate who can make their thinking visible in an interview will almost always beat the candidate who only describes what they did.\n\nThe Four Failure Modes\n\nBefore we get to what great looks like, it is worth spending a moment on the ways most people go wrong in interviews, because recognizing these patterns in yourself is the first step to correcting them.\n\nRambling. The answer never finds a period. The candidate adds context, then backs up to add something they forgot, then qualifies a point they made three sentences ago, and by the time they stop talking, the interviewer has lost the thread along with their confidence in the candidate. Rambling usually comes from one of two places: either the candidate has not prepared enough to know where the story ends, or they are so anxious about saying the wrong thing that they keep adding more in hopes of landing on the right one.\n\nToo short. The opposite problem, and equally damaging. Some candidates, acutely aware that they do not want to ramble or sound like they are bragging, compress their answers to the point of removing all the substance. The answer is technically accurate but leaves the interviewer with no real sense of what happened, who was involved, what the stakes were, or how impressive the result was.\n\nFuzzy. The story is kept at too high a level, too impressionistic, too much gesture and not enough specific detail. Think about the difference between a black and white photograph and one in full color. You can make out the shapes in black and white, you can tell something happened, but the color is what makes it real and memorable and worth looking at. Fuzzy stories are the black and white version of something that should be in color.\n\nGeneric. The answer could have come from almost anyone with a similar job title or function. “We ran an outbound campaign and got solid results.” What does that tell anyone? There is nothing particular to this person, this situation, this team, this problem. Generic answers signal that the candidate either did not do distinctive work, or does not know how to make distinctive work visible. Either impression is harmful.\n\nIrrelevant. The story itself may be strong, well-told, and full of good numbers, but it has not been connected to what this interviewer cares about. The candidate is proud of the accomplishment, and rightly so, but they have not done the work of bridging the gap between what they did at their last company and what this company is trying to solve. The interviewer walks away thinking: that was interesting, but I am not sure what it has to do with us.\n\nThese failure modes are not obscure. They show up in nearly every interview, and most people recognize themselves in at least one. The good news is that all of them have a specific and learnable fix, and the STAR format is where we start.\n\nThe STAR Format — and One Important Modification\n\nThe STAR format is not new, and most people in an active job search are already familiar with the basic idea. What makes it worth revisiting is both what it does well and what traditional STAR leaves out.\n\nWhat it does well: it imposes structure on an experience that, told naturally, tends to sprawl. There is a beginning, a middle, and an end, and the end must produce a result. That discipline alone makes a story more concise, clearer, and more compelling than the unstructured version almost every time. Think of it as a container that forces you to decide what matters before you open your mouth.\n\nThe traditional rendering is Situation, Tasks, Action, Result.\n\nBob’s version changes the T from Tasks to Thought Process. This is not a small change. It is the whole game.\n\nTasks tell the interviewer what you did. Thought process tells them how you think, and how you think is what they are evaluating when they ask you to tell them about a time you navigated a difficult situation. When a candidate says “I decided to conduct one-on-ones with each team member,” that is a task. When a candidate says “I knew before designing any solution I needed to understand the problem from both sides, so I started with structured one-on-ones to separate what people were saying from what they were experiencing.” That is thought process. It demonstrates a framework. It shows that this person approaches problems systematically, gathers information before drawing conclusions, and makes decisions based on what they learn. That is the thing the interviewer is trying to determine: is this the kind of mind we want working on our problems?\n\nRather than claim you are a creative problem solver or a strategic thinker, you show them, through the thought process section of your story, how you think. And showing is always worth more than claiming.\n\nSome frameworks that tend to surface well in the thought process section:\n\nWhat / So What / Now What\n\nPeople, Process, Technology\n\nRight People, Doing the Right Things, the Right Way\n\nVision, Alignment, Execution\n\nAbility, Resources, Commitment\n\nYou do not need to announce the framework by name. You just need to use it. The interviewer will feel the difference between someone who is thinking out loud and someone who actually owns a repeatable way of solving problems.\n\nBefore and After — What This Looks Like in Practice\n\nHere is the same story told two ways, and I want you to pay close attention to what changes between them and why it matters.\n\nThe fuzzy version:\n\nSituation: I came into a new role and saw some issues with team dynamics. People weren’t really working together well or very engaged.\n\nThinking: I thought we should do something about the low morale and stuff, so I decided maybe we could use some new tools or training to help. I also thought about how to have the older and younger team members work together somehow.\n\nAction: We tried several things. Some technology was brought in, but not everyone was happy with it at first. We kind of started a mentorship program, but it was pretty organic. I talked to a lot of people and tried to make them feel better about the changes.\n\nResult: After a while, I think things got a bit better. People seemed happier, and I guess we were doing our jobs more efficiently. I don’t have the exact numbers, but I feel like we made a difference.\n\nRead that back and notice what is happening at a sentence level. “Kind of started.” “Pretty organic.” “I think things got a bit better.” “I feel like we made a difference.” Every sentence hedges. There is no ownership, no framework, no data, no result worth remembering. The word organic is worth calling out specifically: in a story context, organic almost always means there was no real plan. Things just sort of happened. Be careful with that word.\n\nIn some form or another, this is how a meaningful percentage of experienced, talented people tell their stories in interviews. Not because they did not do good work, but because they have not been trained to make good work visible.\n\nThe improved version:\n\nSituation: I inherited a team with an internal engagement score of 52%. The veterans were resistant to a technology transition the company was undertaking, and the younger members felt the work was not giving them what they needed professionally.\n\nThinking: Before designing any solution, I conducted one-on-ones with every team member, because I wanted to make sure people felt heard and I needed to understand the actual drivers rather than my assumptions about them. What I learned was specific: 66% of the more tenured team members felt their experience wasn’t being respected, while fully half of the younger members said the lack of modern tools made the work feel less interesting and less meaningful.\n\nAction: Based on what I learned, I designed a two-part response. We launched a bi-weekly mutual mentorship program we called The Bridge, pairing experienced and newer members in both directions so that institutional knowledge could flow one way and technology fluency the other. And I introduced automation technology that eliminated the most tedious routine tasks, starting with timesheets, which had been a consistent source of frustration.\n\nResult: Over the next six months, production efficiency increased 25%, representing approximately $3 million in annualized gains.\n\nThe same amount of time to tell. Completely different impression of the person telling it. The thinking is visible. The data is there. The choices are explained. The result is real and specific. And the listener can imagine what this person would do if they encountered a similar problem at their company.\n\nThat is the difference between a black and white picture and one in full color.\n\nWhen You Do Not Have the Numbers\n\nThis question comes up in every group, and it deserves a direct answer because the instinct most people have is the right instinct applied in the wrong direction.\n\nMany people feel that if they cannot get to an exact, auditable, two-decimal-point figure, they should say nothing quantitative at all. That feels like integrity. But what it actually does is force the interviewer into the worst possible position: guessing. And what they guess is almost always less impressive than the reality.\n\nThe right move is order of magnitude. If the result was somewhere between three and five million dollars in savings, say between three and five million dollars. You are not going to be audited. What the listener needs is a frame of reference. Was this a ten-thousand-dollar impact or a ten-million-dollar impact? Those are very different conversations about very different candidates.\n\nTwo practical paths when you cannot pin down a number. First, give a range you feel confident is honest. If you know it was somewhere in the 70 to 80 percent range, say it was between 70 and 80 percent. Second, reach back to former colleagues who were part of the project. Use it as a reason to reconnect. “Do you remember what ended up happening with that initiative?” You will often find that someone on the team knows how things turned out, and they will be glad you asked. We covered this in the resume lesson, and the same principle applies here.\n\nAnd in cases where the story is older and the precise figure has faded from memory, it is completely appropriate to say: “I believe it was approximately 12%. If you would like the exact figure I am happy to look it up and follow up with you.” That is not weakness. That is integrity, and it signals to the interviewer that you are someone who cares about giving accurate information and is willing to do the extra work to provide it.\n\nThe Clarification Question\n\nThis is one of the most powerful and most underused moves in interviewing, and it works on three levels at once.\n\nWhen a question is broad, like “tell me about your philosophy on product management” or “how do you think about the use of data,” the natural instinct is to pick an interpretation and charge in. The more sophisticated move is to pause and ask a clarification question before you answer.\n\nSomething like: “Great question. Before I answer, I want to make sure I address what you’re most interested in. Are you thinking about this from an innovation perspective, a go-to-market perspective, or is there a particular aspect of it that’s most relevant to what you’re working on here?”\n\nNotice what just happened. Before saying a single substantive word about your answer, you have demonstrated expertise by naming the dimensions that exist within that topic. The interviewer can already see that you understand the domain well enough to know it is multifaceted. And almost always, what comes back is not just a clarification of what they mean, but an explanation of why they are asking, which means you now know the problem underneath the question, and you can answer it with real precision rather than hoping you guessed correctly.\n\nThere is also a secondary benefit worth naming: the clarification question gives you a moment to breathe. The pressure of a live interview can make even the most prepared candidate reach for the wrong story or lose the thread before they find it. While the interviewer is explaining what they are really after, you have a professional reason to settle, get your wits back, and reach for the right story rather than the first one that comes to mind.\n\nNever feel that asking for clarification signals weakness or lack of preparation. It signals the opposite. It signals that you care about giving a relevant answer rather than any answer, and that you understand the difference between those two things.\n\nRemixing — A Preview\n\nOne skill that builds naturally on top of what we have covered here is the ability to take the same story and tell it differently depending on who is in the room. The CFO wants the financial headline. The CEO wants the strategic arc. The CHRO wants the human dimension. The melody of the story is the same. The facts do not change, but the emphasis shifts based on what your audience cares about most.\n\nWe will go deep on this in the next lesson, including how to build and use your story playlist. For now, the important thing is to get the foundation right: clear structure, visible thought process, honest numbers, and the ability to connect your experience to their world. When those four things are in place, remixing is a natural next step.\n\nPreparation Is What Creates Poise\n\nThere is a reason that professional athletes, musicians, and surgeons all share one thing in common: they practice far more than they perform. The performance is the easy part, once the preparation is deep enough. The pressure does not disappear, but it has somewhere to land.\n\nThe same principle applies here. When you have not prepared, the anxiety of an interview has nothing to push against. The nerves take over. The words come out rough. You lose the thread mid-sentence and the hedging language fills the gap. You know what I mean: kind of, sort of, I think things got a bit better. When you have taken the time to write your stories out, internalize them, and say them out loud until they flow, something different happens. When the question comes in, in whatever form it takes, you recognize the shape of it and you know where to go. The preparation becomes poise. The poise becomes composure. And the composure is what we talked about in the 4 C’s: that quality of grounded confidence that people feel before they can articulate why, that makes the interviewer lean forward rather than check out.\n\nThat is the goal. Not a performance. Not a memorized script. A depth of preparation that lets you be present in the room, respond naturally to what the interviewer is asking, and tell your stories in a way that is clear, specific, compelling, and connected to what they care about.\n\nThree ways to build that preparation before game day:\n\nYour accountability partner. Someone who will listen to your stories, react, and tell you where they lost you. The stakes are low, the feedback is real, and you get comfortable hearing the words come out of your mouth in the presence of another person, which is meaningfully different from rehearsing in your head.\n\nAI voice tools. Ask an AI voice tool to play the role of an interviewer. Tell it what format you are using, what type of story you are practicing, and what you want feedback on. It will tell you what landed and where you started to drift. It is available any time and will not soften the feedback out of politeness.\n\nLow-risk interviews. If you have the chance to interview for a role you are not certain you want, wrong geography, not quite the right company, take it. Use it as a dress rehearsal. You cannot simulate the pressure of a real interview any other way, and the experience will make every subsequent interview sharper.\n\nReflection\n\nWrite out your current top five professional accomplishments in XYZ format. Now convert each one into a full STAR story with the T as Thought Process. Do you have enough in the Thinking section to make your framework visible, or does it still read more like a list of tasks?\n\nFor each story, ask yourself: what is the Situation in one sentence? What was my Thought Process, and does it reveal a repeatable framework? What specific Actions did I take? What was the measurable Result?\n\nWhich of the four failure modes do you tend toward — rambling, too short, fuzzy, or generic? What is one concrete thing you can do differently in your next story to address it?\n\nThink about the numbers in your stories. For any result you cannot pin down precisely, what range could you give that would be honest and useful? Is there a former colleague worth reaching out to who might remember what happened with a project you worked on together?\n\nBuild your playlist. What are the twelve stories that cover the bingo card of questions you are most likely to face in your target roles? Write the titles down now, even if you have not fully developed all of them yet.\n\nPractice one story out loud today — with your accountability partner, with an AI voice tool, or just to yourself on a walk. Notice where it gets tight, where you lose the thread, and where you tend to trail off without finding a period.\n\nLesson 9B — People Hire People\n\nYou now have the STAR format. You understand thought process, the four failure modes, the clarification question, and what preparation does for your poise in the room. That is the craft of telling a single story well. But there is something that sits underneath all of it, something that no framework fully captures, and it is the thing that hiring decisions ultimately turn on.\n\nPeople hire people.\n\nNot resumes. Not credentials. Not even accomplishments, in isolation. A human being sitting across a table or a screen is deciding whether they want to work with you, whether they can picture you in the room with their team, whether you are the kind of person they want to say yes to. And the mistake most candidates make is dialing down their humanity in the very moment they need it most, because the stakes feel too high to risk being themselves.\n\nIn getting too conservative, they blow it in a quieter way. By becoming forgettable.\n\nThis lesson is about the other side of the interviewing equation: not just what you say, but who you are when you say it. The five dimensions we are going to cover here are:\n\nProficiency\n\nPassion\n\nPersonality\n\nPerspiration\n\nPotential\n\nTaken together, they are really just a framework for being yourself with intention. Bringing more of who you actually are into a room where many people bring less.\n\nProficiency — Table Stakes, Not the Finish Line\n\nProficiency is what got you the interview. Your resume communicated that you look, on paper, like someone who can do what they need done. The interview itself is the verification exercise. They are testing whether what you wrote down is actually true. SHRM has a term for the opposite: skill phishing, where candidates present competencies they do not actually have. The response to that environment is to be specific, to use real examples, and to demonstrate that you can walk the talk you claimed on paper.\n\nWhat proficiency is not is sufficient. Candidates often spend the entire interview trying to prove their proficiency and leave the other four dimensions almost completely untouched. That is a costly mistake, because the factors we are about to cover actuate at least as heavily on hiring decisions as proficiency does. Proficiency is the floor. What distinguishes the candidate who gets the offer is what they build on top of it.\n\nOne more thing worth naming here: staying current matters. You can demonstrate proficiency in what you have done historically and simultaneously signal that you are paying attention to where your field is going. Knowing what is changing, what tools are emerging, what practices are being disrupted, what the conversation at the leading edge sounds like right now, is itself a form of proficiency. We will come back to this when we get to Potential.\n\nPassion — The Tiebreaker and the Bridge\n\nThe question passion answers is: why do you actually want this? Not the rehearsed version. The real one. What about this company’s mission, its customers, its technology, or its culture resonates with something you actually care about?\n\nPassion matters for two distinct reasons. The first is that it is a tiebreaker. When two candidates are close on proficiency, the one who demonstrably cares about what the company cares about will win. For the other candidate, this is a job. For you, it is something you are aligned to at a deeper level, and the person across the table can feel that difference even when they cannot fully articulate it.\n\nThe second reason is that passion is a bridge. For candidates in transition, moving to a new industry, a new function, or a role that is a stretch on the hard skills, that passion can compensate for a gap in direct experience. You may be a 7 out of 10 on the technical side, but if you truly care about what they care about, and can communicate that without performing it, that will carry real weight. The key phrase is without performing it. Interviewers can feel authentic passion, and they can feel the absence of it. There is no way to fake your way through this particular question.\n\nKnow before you walk in why you want this specific role at this specific company. The candidate who can answer that question with something real and specific is the one who lights up the room.\n\nPersonality — Help Them Like You\n\nPeople want to like you. That sounds obvious, but in a high-stakes interview, candidates systematically suppress the very qualities that would make them likable, because they are afraid of getting something wrong. They dial down the warmth, the humor, the curiosity, the personal detail, and the result is that the person across from them is talking to a candidate rather than a human being. Candidates are easy to forget.\n\nWhen you let your personality come through, when you notice the guitar on the wall and ask about it, when you make a real connection over something you spotted on their LinkedIn profile, when you make an appropriate joke or simply smile naturally, you become a person they remember. The hiring manager is also doing something the interview process does not formally acknowledge: they are imagining you in the room with their team. Can they picture it? Will you make the environment better? A candidate who is warm, curious, and present communicates something about what it will feel like to work alongside them.\n\nOne practical way to let your personality come through is in your Tell Me About Yourself. Take a piece of your real life outside of work, a hobby, an interest, an experience, and connect it meaningfully to your professional themes. The example I use on myself: I like doing crossword puzzles. Crossword puzzles have a strategic element, but you also take the little bits you do know to figure out the parts you do not, and I thrive in environments where that kind of thinking matters. Now that is part of how I describe my value proposition. And nobody forgets the crossword puzzle person. That is exactly the point.\n\nThis is also where your assessment results can do more work than candidates often realize. Rather than claiming “I am someone who naturally builds cross-functional relationships,” you can point to something objective: “One of the things the Affintus assessment surfaced for me was a strong orientation toward collaboration, and here is where I have seen that come to life.” You are not making a claim. You are making a claim and pointing to third-party validation, and that is evidence-based confidence, which is the definition of confidence we talked about in the 4 C’s. The assessments you took in the Personal Branding section were never just about building your resume. They are a vocabulary for talking about who you are in an interview with something real to point to.\n\nDo not see letting your personality through as a risk. See it as a magnet.\n\nPerspiration — There Is No Substitute for Hard Work\n\nThis is the bonus P, added to the original four because the moment calls for it.\n\nWhat I hear consistently from hiring managers is that they are looking for people who want to work, who show up, and who see things through to completion even when no one requires it. A candidate who communicates a durable work ethic stands in stark relief. That quality is noticeable in an interview, and it is worth communicating deliberately rather than hoping it comes through on its own.\n\nFor those who are navigating concerns about ageism, this P is worth leaning into deliberately. Communicate clearly that there is a lot of gas left in this tank, that you like to work hard, that you have always worked hard, and that you are looking forward to doing it again. That is a message worth sending. Not defensively. Confidently.\n\nPotential — Someone They Can Grow Around\n\nPotential has two dimensions, and both are worth preparing for.\n\nThe first is curiosity and agile learning. Ask leaders what they most look for when building a team, and natural curiosity comes back as the answer more often than almost anything else. It is not just whether you are good at what you do today. It is whether you will keep getting better as the world keeps changing, because the world will keep changing whether or not you are keeping up with it. Today is the slowest day of the rest of your life. The pace and the magnitude of change are not slowing down, and mastery of what exists today does not guarantee relevance in three years.\n\nIf you are going to claim curiosity, and you should, be ready to back it up with specifics. What podcasts are you listening to? What is the last book you read and what did you take from it? What are you actively learning right now that you did not know a year ago? The word curious, said alone, means nothing. The conversation that shows a curious mind says everything. And again, your assessment results are worth bringing back here. If CliftonStrengths or Affintus surfaced a strong learning orientation, that is a credible third-party anchor for the claim you are making about yourself.\n\nThe second dimension of potential is scalability. The company is not just filling a seat for today. They are making a bet on where this person is going. Will you grow with them? As their teams expand and they need people who can take on more responsibility, are you someone they can build around? Show them the ceiling is high. Show them you have not found the top yet, and that you have no particular interest in finding it anytime soon.\n\nBe Yourself — That Is the Whole Point\n\nThe five Ps taken together are not a performance framework. They are a permission structure.\n\nThe temptation in a high-stakes interview is to become a more careful, more conservative, more buttoned-up version of yourself, to suppress anything that feels risky in favor of projecting a safe and professional surface. And in doing so, many talented people become difficult to distinguish from every other qualified candidate in the pile.\n\nWhat the five Ps are really asking you to do is show your proficiency through specific examples rather than vague claims. Communicate passion rather than performing interest. Let your personality come through rather than tamping it down out of fear. Demonstrate a real work ethic through the stories you tell and the way you show up. And signal that you are still on an upward trajectory, that you are curious, that you are learning, that you have more ahead of you than behind.\n\nNone of this asks you to be someone you are not. It asks you to bring more of who you actually are into a room where many people bring less.\n\nThat is the whole idea. People hire people. Walk in like one.\n\nReflection\n\nAs you think about your next interview, where are you spending the most preparation time? If the honest answer is proficiency, what would it look like to give equal attention to the other four Ps?\n\nWrite out your actual answer to “why do you want this job?” for each company on your target list. The candidate who can answer that question with something real and specific is the one who lights up the room.\n\nWhat aspect of your personality — a hobby, an interest, a personal story — connects meaningfully to your professional themes and would make you memorable? Work it into your Tell Me About Yourself before your next conversation.\n\nHow would you demonstrate a real work ethic in an interview rather than just claiming it? What specific examples from your career show someone going above and beyond, or seeing something through when no one required them to?\n\nIf someone asked you right now to back up a claim of curiosity, what would you say? What are you actually reading, listening to, or learning?\n\nGo back to your assessment results. What do they surface about your natural wiring that would be useful to weave into answers about personality, curiosity, or potential? Practice saying it in your own voice until it sounds like you rather than a report.\n\nLesson 10 — STAR in Practice: The Playlist and the Framework\n\nIn the previous lesson we built the foundation: the STAR format, the shift from Tasks to Thought Process, the four failure modes, and what a well-told story looks like versus a fuzzy one. This lesson is about what you do with a portfolio of stories. How you build a playlist that covers the terrain of likely interview questions. How you think about the two different kinds of questions you will face and what each one is really asking for. And how you practice in a way that makes the preparation show up as poise rather than performance.\n\nTo set the stage: if STAR gives you the container for a single story, this lesson gives you the system for deploying many stories, in any order, for any interviewer, in any context.\n\nA Quick Recap: The Framework\n\nThe framework is Situation, Thought Process, Action, Result. The Situation creates stakes. The Thought Process is your intellectual fingerprint, the part that shows how you think rather than just what you did. The Action is specific and concrete. The Result is quantified. Together, they answer the question every interviewer is asking: is this the kind of mind we want working on our problems?\n\nWith that foundation in place, the next question is: which stories do you bring into the room?\n\nFrom Black and White to Color\n\nYou have already seen what the difference between a weak and a strong STAR story looks like, in the previous lesson. The fuzzy version hedges at every turn, keeps the thought process invisible, and leaves the result unquantified. The improved version shows the thinking, earns the result with specific data, and lets the listener imagine you solving their problem. The difference between those two versions is preparation, and the discipline to go back to your stories and make them specific before you walk into the room. That is the work this lesson continues.\n\nOn Quantification — You Don’t Need the Exact Number\n\nThe most common reason candidates stay vague in their STAR stories is the same reason we discussed in the resume lesson: they don’t remember the exact number, and they don’t want to say something inaccurate.\n\nIntegrity is exactly the right instinct. But the response to not knowing the exact number is not to say nothing. It is to give an honest range or estimate.\n\nIf you know it was somewhere between 70% and 80%, say that. If you know the project was worth somewhere in the range of three to five million dollars, say that. If you can’t remember the precise engagement score but you know it went from the low 50s to the mid-70s, say that. A range that is honest is far more useful to an interviewer than a silence that communicates either poor record-keeping or lack of ownership of results.\n\nAnd if the number truly isn’t accessible to you, use AI to help reconstruct a reasonable frame of reference. That gives you an order-of-magnitude context that makes your story more credible without fabricating anything.\n\nThe other path is to reach back to former colleagues who were part of the project. As we covered in Lessons 3 and 5, those conversations do double duty. They surface the downstream outcomes of work you may never have seen the results of, and they reconnect you with people in your network. Sometimes the number you couldn’t remember, Julie has. Sometimes Julie doesn’t know either, but she knows Charles does. Use your network.\n\nAsking a Clarifying Question Is Not a Weakness\n\nOne of the most underused techniques in interviewing: when you’re not sure exactly what the interviewer is asking, ask for clarification before you answer.\n\nNot only is this acceptable. It is often advantageous.\n\nIf you answer the wrong question beautifully, you’ve accomplished nothing. Getting clarity on what they’re actually asking ensures your story is relevant. But there’s a second benefit most candidates don’t realize: the way you ask the clarifying question itself demonstrates expertise.\n\nIf an interviewer asks “tell me about your philosophy on product management” and you respond with “great question, are you most interested in the innovation side, the go-to-market approach, or how I think about prioritization across competing stakeholder needs?” You’ve just revealed that you understand product management well enough to know there are meaningfully different lenses through which to see it. That’s not buying time. That’s showing your work.\n\nAsking for clarification also buys you a moment to think. While they’re answering, your mind is reaching into the playlist of stories you’ve prepared and finding the right one. You arrive at your answer having had ten extra seconds to think, and those ten seconds often make the difference between a story that lands and one that rambles.\n\nThe Playlist — About Twelve Stories\n\nCandidates often ask: how many STAR stories do I need?\n\nThe answer is not one hundred. You don’t need a story for every possible question. You need a playlist of approximately twelve stories that cover enough of the likely question territory that you can handle the vast majority of what you’ll be asked.\n\nTwelve strong, specific, well-prepared stories, each with a clear Situation, a visible Thought Process, concrete Actions, and quantified Results, will serve you across more interviews and more questions than a hundred vague ones ever could. The goal is depth and specificity, not volume.\n\nHow do you pick the twelve? Start with your Professional Milestones from your resume. Those are already your greatest hits. Add stories that demonstrate different capabilities: leadership, collaboration, managing through adversity, driving innovation, delivering results under pressure, navigating ambiguity. Then think about your target roles and what those interviewers are most likely to probe. AI can help you generate the likely question categories for any given role and level, and from there you can audit your playlist for gaps.\n\nIn Lesson 10B we’ll cover how to take those twelve stories and remix them, adapting the same core story to different audiences and different questions. For now, the work is building the playlist and making each story as specific and as vivid as you can make it.\n\nTwo Kinds of Questions — One Framework\n\nMost interview questions fall into one of two categories. Understanding the difference, and knowing how to handle each, is one of the most useful things you can take into any interview room.\n\nBehavioral questions ask about the past. Tell me about a time when you had to lead through significant change. Describe a situation where you disagreed with your manager. Give me an example of a time you failed and what you learned from it. These are the questions STAR was built for. Your answer draws from real experience, with a real situation, a real thought process, real actions, and a real result.\n\nSituational or hypothetical questions ask about the future, or about a constructed scenario the interviewer presents. How would you approach building a team from scratch? What would you do in the first ninety days of this role? If you inherited a department with low morale and declining performance, where would you start? These questions have no past story to draw from. The interviewer is asking you to reason through something in real time.\n\nHere is what makes this important: situational questions are not a different kind of interview challenge. They are a more direct version of the same challenge. Behavioral questions ask you to demonstrate how you think through the texture of a real story. Situational questions ask you to demonstrate how you think directly, without the story as the vehicle.\n\nWhich means the answer to a situational question is the Thought Process. Your framework is the answer.\n\nThe candidate who says “well, I’d probably start by talking to some people and getting a feel for things” is giving an unstructured answer that reveals an unstructured mind. The candidate who says “my instinct whenever I inherit a struggling team is to think in three layers: first understand the people, then understand the process, then understand the technology, because those three almost always interact and you can’t fix one without understanding the others” is revealing something entirely different. A mind that operates with structure, consistency, and, crucially, transferability. That’s a mind worth hiring.\n\nThis is why frameworks matter so much.\n\nA framework is a repeatable way of thinking about a category of problem. Some examples worth knowing, and more importantly, worth examining to see which ones you actually use:\n\nWhat, So What, Now What\n\nPeople, Process, Technology\n\nStart with the customer and work backward\n\nThe Five Forces\n\nJobs to be done\n\nSituation, Complication, Resolution\n\nThe specific framework matters less than the fact that you have one: that you approach categories of challenge with disciplined, structured thinking rather than improvising in the moment.\n\nMcKinsey and firms like it get paid extraordinary fees to bring frameworks to their clients. What a framework signals, when you deploy one in an interview, is exactly what those firms are selling: structured thinking. The ability to see a problem clearly, decompose it logically, and navigate it consistently. That is what companies are buying when they hire leaders.\n\nBefore your next interview, take ten minutes and make a short list of the frameworks you actually use. Not the ones you’ve read about. The ones that are actually yours: the ways of approaching problems that you’ve internalized over the course of your career, that you could articulate and defend under questioning, that you could teach to someone else. Those frameworks are your answer to every situational question you’ll ever be asked. They are your operating system, made visible.\n\nA great answer to a situational question often ends with a real example. Once you’ve articulated your framework, here’s how I think about this category of challenge, you can say: “And let me give you a concrete example of how that’s actually played out.” Then you tell a STAR story.\n\nWhich means your playlist of twelve STAR stories and your inventory of frameworks are not two separate things to prepare. They are two sides of the same preparation. The frameworks answer the situational questions. The stories answer the behavioral ones. And the best answers use both: framework first, story as proof.\n\nPractice — Perfect Practice Makes Perfect\n\nOne of the things that distinguishes truly compelling interview performance from merely adequate performance is not intelligence, not experience, not even preparation in the abstract. It is practice, specifically the experience of hearing yourself say the words out loud.\n\nCandidates often prepare for interviews by thinking about their answers in their head. The problem is that the version of a story that exists in your head and the version that comes out of your mouth when you’re sitting in front of a hiring manager under pressure are often very different things. The head version is smooth and articulate. The spoken version, for many people, is where the rambling starts, where the ums accumulate, where the point gets lost.\n\nThe solution is to practice speaking, not just thinking. And AI has made this dramatically more accessible than it used to be.\n\nUse an AI voice tool, ChatGPT Voice, Claude, or Gemini, whichever you prefer, and practice your STAR stories out loud. Say the words. Let the tool give you feedback. Ask it to push back on your answers the way a tough interviewer would. Ask it to probe on the Thought Process element specifically, because that’s where answers most often go thin.\n\nUse your accountability partner from Career Club Corner, someone who knows you, who has your best interests at heart, and who will tell you the truth about whether your story actually landed or whether it just felt like it did to you. These are different things.\n\nConsider taking a low-stakes interview with a company you’re less excited about just for the reps. There is no substitute for actually doing it. Every interview you take, even one that doesn’t result in an offer you want, makes you sharper for the one that does.\n\nPerfect practice makes perfect. Preparation is what takes the pressure out of the room and allows you to be poised, to show up as the full human being we talked about in Lesson 9, rather than a nervous candidate trying to keep it together.\n\nA Note on Bringing It Together\n\nThe STAR framework is not a script. It is a structure, a discipline that keeps you from rambling, keeps you from going too short, and ensures that every story you tell has a point and a payoff. Once you’ve internalized it, you won’t be thinking about the framework in the room. You’ll just be telling a story well.\n\nAnd when an interviewer asks you about an accomplishment you’re proud of, and you smile because you actually prepared for this question, and you open with: “I’m glad you asked. As I was going through your job description, geographic expansion jumped out as a priority, and that reminds me of a time at...” and that is not a rehearsed line. That is what preparedness actually looks like from the outside.\n\nThat’s the goal. Not a perfect performance. A conversation between two people, one of whom has done the work to show up ready.\n\nReflection\n\nPull out your resume’s Professional Milestones section. For each bullet, ask yourself: could I tell this as a full STAR story — with a specific Situation, a visible Thought Process, concrete Actions, and a quantified Result? If not, which element is missing?\n\nThink about your last interview. Where did your answers go vague or generic? What specific detail could you add to make that story come alive?\n\nWhere in your STAR stories is your Thought Process most visible? Where is it most thin? What frameworks do you actually think in — and have you ever named them out loud in an interview?\n\nDo you have approximately twelve stories ready? Map them against the likely question categories for your target role. Where are the gaps?\n\nMake a list of the frameworks you actually use. Could you articulate each one clearly enough to use it as the answer to a situational question? Could you then bridge to a real STAR story as proof?\n\nHave you practiced your stories out loud — not just in your head? If not, who will you practice with this week?\n\nIs there a number in one of your key stories that you’ve been leaving vague because you’re not sure of the exact figure? What would a reasonable, honest estimate be — and who might help you reconstruct it?\n\nLesson 10 — Remixing and SCOPE: One Story, Many Dimensions\n\nWe have spent the last two lessons building the foundation: the STAR format, the shift from Tasks to Thought Process, the four failure modes, the clarification question, the importance of preparation. All of that is the craft of telling a single story well. This lesson is about what you do with a portfolio of stories, and how to make a small, well-developed set of them feel like the right answer to almost any question an interviewer could ask.\n\nThe Playlist Principle\n\nThe question that comes up in almost every group is: how many stories do I need? The honest answer is that you do not need one hundred stories for one hundred questions. What you need is a playlist of roughly twelve well-built STAR stories that cover the full range of likely interview topics. A good playlist includes at minimum:\n\nA significant achievement\n\nA failure and what you learned from it\n\nA time you led without formal authority\n\nA difficult collaboration\n\nA moment of strategic impact\n\nA situation where you had to navigate ambiguity or conflict\n\nThe playlist is finite. It is manageable. And the skill that sits on top of it is what makes it feel infinite.\n\nThat skill is remixing.\n\nThe DJ Metaphor\n\nA remixed song has the same melody. What changes is the beat: the emphasis, the texture, the part of the track that gets the most airtime in this particular version for this particular audience. A great DJ does not play a different song for each crowd. They read the room and adjust what they are doing with the same raw material, turning up the bass for one listener and bringing the tempo down for another, while the underlying song remains exactly what it was.\n\nThat is what we are building toward in this lesson. One story, adjusted in emphasis and focus depending on who is listening and what they need to hear. The facts do not change. The lens through which you present them does. And learning to shift that lens fluidly, in real time, based on who is sitting across from you, is one of the most sophisticated things you can do in an interview.\n\nRemixing in Action — Three Interviewers, One Story\n\nBefore we go into the framework, three simple examples to make this concrete.\n\nTake a salesperson who finished the year at 140% of quota. A strong result by any reasonable standard. Now watch what happens when that same story gets told to three different people in three different rooms.\n\nThe CFO. A CFO’s first instinct when they hear a sales number is not admiration. It is skepticism. Salespeople will move volume if that is how they are measured, regardless of whether the volume was profitable. The CFO wants to know whether hitting that number actually made money. Was the margin healthy? Did you protect pricing? Did you sell the right mix, or did you discount your way to the top of the leaderboard? When you are telling this story to a CFO, lead with the financial discipline. The 140% is the headline. The profitability is the story.\n\nThe CEO. The CEO is thinking about strategy and trajectory. A strong sales year is good news, but what they want to understand is whether it moved the company forward in a way that matters. Did the growth open a new market? Did it put a competitor on the back foot? Did it advance one of the company’s three big strategic priorities for the year, or was it just a good year in an existing lane? When you are telling this story to a CEO, lead with the strategic dimension of what you achieved and why it matters beyond the number itself.\n\nThe CHRO. The CHRO is thinking about people and culture, and specifically about whether your path to that number left damage in its wake. Some salespeople are brilliant jerks. They hit their targets and leave scorched earth behind them, running through colleagues in product, finance, and operations to make their quarter. The CHRO wants to know which kind you are. Were you a good collaborator? Did you bring people along? Did you make the culture around you better on the way to your result, or just better for yourself? When you are telling this story to a CHRO, lead with the collaboration and the culture, and let the number do its work quietly in the background.\n\nSame story. Same facts. Same result. Three completely different emphases. That is remixing.\n\nSCOPE — One Story, Five Dimensions\n\nTo help structure the remixing thinking, here is a framework: SCOPE. Each letter represents a dimension that most interview questions are trying to get at in one form or another. A well-built STAR story can be examined through any of these five lenses, and the best stories in your playlist will naturally touch several of them. The discipline is learning to recognize which lens the interviewer is looking through and adjusting your emphasis accordingly.\n\nS — Strategy. What were the business outcomes? Was your solution scalable, not a one-off piece of beautiful work that could never be repeated, but something the company could build on and extend? And most importantly: what frameworks did you bring to the problem? Frameworks are the most underused dimension of a STAR story and the one that most powerfully demonstrates strategic thinking. McKinsey gets paid extraordinary fees to bring frameworks to clients. When you can say “I approach this kind of problem using What/So What/Now What” or “I think in terms of People, Process, and Technology,” you are showing that your thinking is portable, repeatable, and durable rather than lucky or situational. People often struggle to name their frameworks, and many do not realize they have them. If you can surface yours even a little, it will work strongly in your favor.\n\nC — Culture. Are you a good cultural fit? Can the interviewer picture you in the room with the team they already have? This dimension covers collaboration, mentoring, and leadership style. For individual contributors, the question is whether you work well alongside others. For leaders, the question is whether you help the team work better together, both within itself and across functions. For those who are more seasoned, being able to talk about mentoring, both giving it and receiving it, is increasingly valued. Know your leadership style before you walk in. You will be asked about it, and a real answer is infinitely more compelling than a platitude.\n\nO — Oneself. This is where the hardest and most important questions live, and where candidates often either dodge or over-confess. Tell me about your greatest failure. What is your biggest weakness? What did you learn about yourself through a difficult period? These questions are not designed to trip you up. They are probing for humility, self-awareness, resilience, and the capacity to keep growing. When you acknowledge a real shortcoming and then describe honestly what you have done about it and how you stay mindful of it, you communicate something that is rarer than most candidates realize: that you know yourself and that you are willing to say so. Humility is not thinking less of yourself. It is thinking of yourself less. And the research on what distinguishes great leaders is unambiguous on this point.\n\nP — Passion. Why do you want this? What lights you up about it? This dimension matters more than candidates often appreciate, and it matters most precisely in the situations where candidates tend to underweight it: career transitions, stretch roles, situations where the technical fit is a 7 out of 10 rather than a perfect match. Passion is a bridge. It will carry you over a gap in hard skills if it is real and the interviewer can feel it. What it cannot do is work if it is performed. The interviewer can feel that too. When someone asks you why you want this job, they deserve a real answer — what specifically about this company, its customers, its mission, or its work moves you. When you can show that rather than recite it, that is the kind of moment that tips a hiring decision.\n\nE — Expertise. The table stakes. Hard skills, specialization, depth of domain knowledge, credibility in the craft. Your functional manager needs to know you can do the job at the level they need it done. A peer interviewer is testing whether you really understand the work, or just know how to talk about it. This is where specific tools, methodologies, and technical fluency come in. Many candidates lead almost entirely with expertise and leave everything else behind, which is understandable. It is the most familiar ground. The reminder is that expertise is necessary but rarely sufficient, and that reading the room to understand what the interviewer needs most is itself a sign of expertise.\n\nPutting SCOPE to Work — With a Little Help\n\nHere is a practical way to put this framework to use without building anything elaborate from scratch.\n\nTake one of your STAR stories, ideally a high-value one that you already know well, and drop it into the AI tool of your choice. Then give it a prompt along these lines: Here is one of my STAR stories. Using the SCOPE framework, covering Strategy, Culture, Oneself, Passion, and Expertise. Please generate five to ten representative interview questions across each dimension that I might be asked about this story. Then, for each question, suggest how I might frame my response to emphasize the most relevant dimension.\n\nWhat comes back will be a working practice session: questions mapped to dimensions, with suggested angles for how to remix the story depending on what each question is getting at. From there, use your accountability partner or an AI voice tool to say the answers out loud, adjusting emphasis as you go until the remixing starts to feel natural rather than mechanical.\n\nThe goal is not to memorize versions of each story. It is to understand your stories well enough that you can adjust the emphasis in real time, reading the room and giving the person across from you what they need to feel confident about you. The preparation is what makes that possible. The SCOPE framework is the map.\n\nThe Weakness Question — A Model for Getting It Right\n\nThis question deserves its own moment because it trips people up in a specific and consistent way. The question takes various forms. What is your greatest weakness, tell me about a significant failure, describe a time when things did not go the way you planned, and it tends to produce one of two bad answers: either a non-answer that nobody believes (“I am a perfectionist,” “I work too hard”), or a real confession that lands with no resolution and leaves the interviewer wondering whether the problem is still live.\n\nThe model that works is: name something real, describe what you have done about it, and close on a note that shows you are still mindful of it. Real. Addressed. Ongoing. That three-part structure communicates humility, self-awareness, and a growth orientation all at once.\n\nThis is also where the assessment work from earlier in the course pays real dividends. The tools we explored in the Personal Branding section, including CliftonStrengths, the Barrett Values assessment, Affintus, and DiSC, are not just useful for building your resume and refining your value proposition. They are a credible, objective basis for talking about what you do well and where your edges are. When you can say “one of the things the CliftonStrengths assessment confirmed for me is that I lead with strategic thinking, and what I have learned over time is that the basement of that strength is a tendency to move past the operational detail faster than some of my colleagues are comfortable with” that is a different kind of answer than a vague admission of imperfection. It is a self-aware, evidence-based answer that shows you have done the work of understanding yourself. That is what the question is designed to surface.\n\nHere is what this looks like in practice. Attention to detail is a real gap. The strength is strategic thinking, connecting dots, working at the level of frameworks and patterns. The basement of that strength is that granular operational detail disengages quickly. So rather than stop there, which would leave the interviewer wondering whether the company will be cleaning up after you, describe what you have done. Surrounding yourself with operationally strong teammates, being intentional about what you own versus what you delegate, building habits and processes that compensate for the gap. Real. Addressed. Ongoing.\n\nYou do not end on a womp-womp. You end on a note of self-awareness and continued growth, which feeds directly into the humility narrative: knowing what you cannot do well is part of knowing how to build the right team around you.\n\nCuriosity — Today Is the Slowest Day of the Rest of Your Life\n\nToday is the slowest day of the rest of your life. The pace of change and the magnitude of change are not slowing down. They are accelerating, and the skills and knowledge that represent mastery today do not guarantee relevance in three years. Companies know this, and the ones that hire well are looking for people who are curious, who keep learning without being told to, who read things that challenge their prior thinking and come to the next conversation a little sharper than they were before.\n\nWhen an interviewer asks what podcasts you listen to, what the last three books you have read were, or what you have learned recently that surprised you, they are not making small talk. They are testing whether you are that kind of person. The way to answer is with specifics, not generalities. Claiming curiosity is not the same as demonstrating it. Be ready to point to something real.\n\nRemixing Is a Skill, Not a Gift\n\nIt would be easy to read this lesson and conclude that remixing is something certain people are naturally good at: the ones who can read a room effortlessly, who seem to know instinctively what each person needs to hear, who adjust on the fly without appearing to. And there are people for whom this comes more naturally than it does for others. But that is not the whole story, and it is not a useful place to leave it.\n\nRemixing is emotional intelligence and situational intelligence working together. Emotional intelligence is the ability to read what another person is feeling and needing in a given moment. Situational intelligence is the ability to understand the context well enough to know what kind of answer will land. Neither of these is a fixed trait that you either have or do not have. Both of them can be developed through practice, reflection, and preparation.\n\nThe candidates who seem to remix effortlessly in an interview are almost always the candidates who have done the most preparation outside of it. They have run their stories through the SCOPE framework. They have thought about who is likely to be in the room and what that person cares about. They have practiced out loud, gotten feedback, adjusted, and practiced again until the adjustment feels natural rather than calculated. The ease in the room is the product of the work done before they walked into it.\n\nRemixing is available to everyone who is willing to prepare for it. It does not require a particular personality type or a natural gift for reading people. It requires exactly what the rest of this course has required: taking the time to do the work before game day, so that when the moment arrives, you are ready for it.\n\nReflection\n\nLook at your current playlist. Do you have stories that cover each of the six topic areas listed at the top of this lesson? If any are missing, identify which ones and build them next.\n\nTake your two or three strongest STAR stories and drop them into your AI tool with the SCOPE prompt described above. Use what comes back as a practice guide, working through the questions out loud until the remixing starts to feel natural.\n\nThink about the Strategy dimension specifically: can you name the frameworks you use? Do you have a consistent, articulate answer to “how do you approach this kind of problem?” If not, spend real time on this. It is one of the highest-leverage investments you can make in your preparation.\n\nGo back to your assessment results from the Personal Branding section. What do they tell you about your strengths, and what do they reveal about the edges of those strengths? Use that as the foundation for your weakness answer rather than starting from scratch.\n\nWrite out your answer to the weakness question using the real/addressed/ongoing structure. Practice it out loud until it sounds like you rather than a rehearsed answer, because the interviewer will know the difference.\n\nFor each company on your target list, write your actual answer to “why do you want this job?” What specifically about this company, its customers, its mission, or its work moves you? If you cannot answer that question with something real, it may be worth examining whether this is the right opportunity.\n\nThink about where curiosity shows up in your life right now. What are you reading, listening to, or learning? Have a specific and honest answer ready, because you will be asked.\n\nPART FIVE\n\nNegotiating\n\nClose the deal on the best possible terms\n\n—\n\nLesson 11 — Closing the Deal: Negotiating\n\nYou made it here. You did the work, you got into the room, you told your stories well, and someone has decided they want you. An offer is coming, or has already arrived. All of it, the attitude work, the brand, the outreach, the interviewing, was preparation for this moment. And this moment has one more skill to learn.\n\nNegotiating is a skill, and you can learn it.\n\nMost people do not negotiate. Estimates suggest only about 15% of people who receive a job offer actually push back on it. The rest accept the first number they are given, assuming that asking for more will irritate the company or somehow put the offer at risk.\n\nHere is what that decision costs. The $10,000 you did not ask for this year becomes the basis for next year’s raise, and the raise after that, and the one after that. Over a career, the compound effect of that one conversation is staggering, potentially hundreds of thousands of dollars left behind. And the company almost always expects a negotiation. They built room into the offer. You are entitled to use it.\n\nBATNA — Your Best Alternative to a Negotiated Agreement\n\nBefore we get into the mechanics, there is a concept worth understanding because it shapes everything else: BATNA. It comes from the landmark negotiating book Getting to Yes, written by Roger Fisher and William Ury at Harvard, and it stands for Best Alternative to a Negotiated Agreement.\n\nYour BATNA is what you have if this deal does not come together. The strength of your BATNA determines your leverage.\n\nThis is why keeping your foot on the gas even when something looks promising is so important. When one opportunity starts to heat up, the natural pull is to focus all of your energy on it, to stop developing other options, to let the pipeline go quiet. And when that happens, you lose the ability to negotiate from a position of strength.\n\nWhen you have other things in motion, two important things happen. First, you have leverage. You can honestly say, without bluffing, that you are pursuing other opportunities and that this one is your preferred path. That changes the dynamic. When companies hear that, timelines often compress, conversations accelerate, and offers sometimes improve on their own. Second, you have emotional resilience. If this particular deal does not come together, something else is in motion. That security shows up in how you carry yourself, and people can feel the difference.\n\nChoices equal leverage. Build the pipeline and keep it full.\n\nYou Are an Investment, Not an Expense\n\nThe mindset that changes everything about how you approach a negotiation is this: you are not asking the company to spend money on you. You are asking them to invest in a return.\n\nWe have talked throughout this course about how every role exists to help the company make money, save money, or mitigate risk. Your STAR stories are full of exactly this kind of evidence. You led a team that generated $3 million in annualized gains. You re-engineered a process that improved throughput by 20%. You identified a risk and built a governance structure that protected the company from a costly audit finding. These are not just stories for an interview. They are the data points for a negotiation.\n\nWhen you can say, here is what I have done, here is the ROI I have produced, and here is what I will bring to this role, you have moved the conversation from what you want to what you are worth. When you can show your work, the conversation changes.\n\nData Is Your Friend\n\nA negotiation built on market data is a fact-based discussion. Come to it prepared.\n\nBefore any compensation conversation, do the research. Salary.com is a solid starting point. Many states now have salary transparency laws that require employers to post the compensation range in the job listing. A quick search will tell you which states have this requirement, and if you are interviewing in one of them, that is valuable public information. AI tools like ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini can synthesize salary data by role, function, geography, company size, and years of experience quickly and reasonably well.\n\nThe goal is to be able to say: based on the research I have done, for someone with my experience, in this function, in this market, the range for a role like this is X to Y. That is a grounded, evidence-based position. Know your number before the conversation starts.\n\nYour Best and Fewest Arguments\n\nThere is a temptation in any high-stakes conversation to build the strongest possible case by accumulating reasons. Ten reasons must be more persuasive than two, the thinking goes. In practice, the opposite tends to be true.\n\nA skilled negotiator on the other side of the table will not be overwhelmed by a long list of reasons. They will find your weakest one and make that the focus of the conversation. And now you are spending your energy defending a point you never needed to make, wondering how you got there. The answer is that you brought it up.\n\nThe discipline is your best and fewest arguments. When you are justifying your compensation ask, two strong data points will do more work than ten mixed ones. When you are explaining why you left a company, one clean and honest reason is more credible than six qualifications strung together. The more you say, the more material you give the other side to work with.\n\nThis applies everywhere in a negotiation, and in interviews too. When a question feels uncomfortable, the instinct is to over-explain in hopes that volume creates conviction. What actually creates conviction is a clear, confident, well-supported answer that stops when it has said what it needs to say. Say what is true, say it well, and stop.\n\nIt Starts on the First Call\n\nThe salary conversation does not begin when the offer arrives. It begins on the very first screener call, when a recruiter or HR professional asks: what were you making in your last role?\n\nWhat you were making in your last role has nothing to do with what this role pays. The company has a budget. They are asking the question to see if you fit within it, and the better move is to redirect the conversation before you anchor to a number. Can you share with me what the budget is for this role? They know what it is. You are simply asking them to share it first, so that the conversation starts from a real number.\n\nIf they ask for your range, be ready with one. Come prepared with a total compensation figure, not just base salary, that reflects the research you have done. State it clearly, anchor toward the higher end of your range, and then be quiet.\n\nSay what it is. And then be quiet.\n\nThis is harder than it sounds. The silence that follows a number is uncomfortable, and the impulse is to keep talking, to qualify, to soften, to add context that was not asked for. Resist it. The other person will fill the silence. Let them.\n\nTotal Compensation — Salary Is Just the Beginning\n\nOne of the most valuable things you can do in a negotiation is expand the aperture beyond salary. Salary is one variable among many, and for some people in some situations, other elements matter more. Here is everything that is on the table:\n\nBase salary\n\nBonus — and importantly, what percentage has actually been paid out in recent years, not just what is offered on paper\n\nSign-on bonus — useful, but because it does not compound year over year, getting money into base salary is worth more over time\n\nTitle — often easier for a company to give than cash, and can matter significantly for your next move\n\nBenefits — the quality of the health plan, what you are actually paying per month, the deductible, the out-of-pocket maximum\n\nRetirement — the 401K match, and whether vesting is immediate or on a schedule\n\nEquity — stock options, RSUs, the vesting schedule, and what the current valuation looks like\n\nPTO — if the company offers unlimited PTO, ask what people actually take on average. Unlimited PTO policies tend to produce lower actual utilization than defined allotments, because people feel uncomfortable using what feels undefined\n\nWork location — the ability to work remotely or on a hybrid schedule can be worth more than a salary increment when you factor in commuting time and cost\n\nProfessional development — conference attendance, continuing education, certifications\n\nAccess to senior leadership — one of the most creative things someone can negotiate is a quarterly check-in with the CEO or a named executive mentor. It costs the company almost nothing, and it puts you on the radar of people who make decisions about what comes next for you\n\nThink about these as pieces of a puzzle. When the cash portion of an offer is not where you want it, other pieces can close the gap in ways that are real and meaningful. Know your priorities before the conversation starts so that you know which trades are worth making.\n\nTone — Would That Be Fair?\n\nEverything we have talked about is the substance of the negotiation. Tone is what makes it work.\n\nA negotiation that feels collaborative produces agreements. The posture you want to bring is: I am excited about this opportunity, I want to make this work, and I want to find something that is right for both of us. That posture signals confidence and professionalism simultaneously, and it gives the person across from you something to say yes to.\n\nThe single best phrase in a negotiation is: would that be fair?\n\nWhen you make a counter-proposal, end it with that question. Everyone wants to be fair. Ending your ask there sets a win-win tone and signals that you have thought about this, done your research, and are proposing something reasonable. The question invites agreement rather than resistance.\n\nYou might also try the inverse: does that seem unfair? When someone pushes back on a request, asking whether your ask strikes them as unfair tends to produce a quick no, and that no is really a yes. Both versions work toward the same destination: clarity on the way to closure.\n\nWho to Negotiate With and How\n\nIn many situations, the offer comes through an HR professional or a recruiter rather than the hiring manager. Understanding this dynamic matters.\n\nThe HR person is the intermediary. They are carrying a message on behalf of the hiring manager, who is the person who actually wants you, who has committed to you as the right candidate, and who has the authority to make adjustments. When a lowball offer comes through HR, reply to the HR person and copy the hiring manager. Warmly. Something like: thank you so much for this. I think there are a few elements we could still work through to find something that works for everyone. Would you be available Wednesday or Thursday for a quick call?\n\nNegotiate by phone or Zoom. Not email. Email strips tone entirely, and in a conversation this important, you want every cue available to you. You want to see their face. You want them to see yours. A live conversation produces information that email never will, and it creates a human dynamic that makes agreement easier to reach.\n\nThe hiring manager has already made a decision. They want you. They have crossed that bridge and they want to get to yes. Keep that in mind as you go in. You are not adversaries. You are two people trying to find a number that works.\n\nA Note on Accepting What Works\n\nAll of this said: an offer is a good thing. And sometimes the right move is to accept it.\n\nIf the offer is close enough, if the other elements of the package are strong, if the role itself is exciting, if the culture feels right and the people are people you want to work alongside, those things have real value too. Know your number, know your priorities, go in prepared, and then make the best decision for you.\n\nThe Value of Knowing Your Value\n\nAll of the work in this course, the convictions, the clarity, the TMAY, the resume, the outreach, the STAR stories, was building toward one thing: a clear, confident, evidence-based answer to the question every employer is implicitly asking. Why you? When you can answer that question with specificity and conviction, when you know what problems you solve, what results you produce, and what you bring that others do not, you have something worth negotiating for.\n\nThe negotiation is where your value proposition does its most concrete and consequential work. Everything that came before was in service of getting you to this table. This is where you make sure that when you arrive, you claim what you have earned.\n\nRemember the salesperson with a quota of one. You have been running a sales process throughout this entire course, and the close is right here. A great salesperson does not discount their product at the finish line. They know what it is worth, they have the data to support it, and they ask for it with confidence and warmth.\n\nYou have done the work. You know your value. Go get paid for it.\n\nReflection\n\nWhat is your BATNA right now? If your most promising opportunity fell through tomorrow, what else is in motion? If the answer is not much, building that pipeline is the best place to start.\n\nBefore your next compensation conversation, do the research. What does the market actually pay for someone with your experience, in your function, in your geography? Build the dataset before you need it.\n\nThink through the full picture of total compensation for a role you are pursuing. Beyond salary, which elements matter most to you? Know the answer before the conversation starts so you know which trades are worth making.\n\nPractice saying a number out loud and then being quiet. Notice how long the silence actually lasts. It is almost always shorter than it feels.\n\nWrite out how you would respond to “what were you making in your last role?” Have the answer ready before the first screener call.\n\nThink about where you would use “would that be fair?” in a negotiation. Practice saying it until it sounds natural coming out of your mouth.\n\nA Final Word\n\nYou came into this course at a moment of transition. Uncertainty has a way of making people feel smaller than they are. What this course has tried to do, from the very first lesson to this one, is give you back a sense of agency: the knowledge that how you show up in a search, what you know about yourself, how deliberately you pursue the right opportunities, and how well you advocate for your own worth, all of it is within your control. You have learned how to keep an even keel through the exhilarating highs and the excruciating lows. You have done the work of understanding what makes you distinctly you, your natural wiring, your values, the problems you are built to solve, and turned all of that self-knowledge into a value proposition that is specific, credible, and yours. You have learned how to network in a way that builds value for both you and the people you meet, how to reach out proactively to companies that should want you before they know they want you, and how to tell your stories in an interview with the kind of clarity and confidence that comes from preparation rather than luck.\n\nTaken together, these are more than job search tactics. They are a set of skills that will serve you for the rest of your professional life. The ability to articulate your value clearly and specifically does not expire when you land. The discipline of building relationships before you need them compounds over decades. The habit of thinking like a salesperson who knows their product, knows their market, and goes after it with confidence rather than waiting for an RFP to arrive is a way of operating that will make you better at almost any role you take on. The people who do the work in this course do not just find their next job. They find it faster, on better terms, with a clearer sense of what they are looking for and why. And they carry those skills into the role they earn.\n\nViktor Frankl, who survived the unimaginable and built a philosophy from the rubble of it, wrote that suffering ceases to be suffering the moment it finds a meaning. A job search is not suffering in Frankl’s sense, but it is a genuine crucible, one that asks you to sit with uncertainty, to face rejection, to keep going when the silence suggests stopping, and to believe in your own value when the market has not yet confirmed it. What you find on the other side of that struggle, if you go through it with intention, is not just a job. It is a sharper sense of who you are, what you want, and what you are worth. That is not a small thing. That is the kind of clarity that many people spend whole careers searching for. You have been building it all along.\n\nAppendix: Resources and Further Reading\n\nThe tools, assessments, books, and communities listed here are organized by lesson so you can find them in context. All downloadable tools from this course are available at career.club.\n\nLesson 1 — Keeping an Even KEEL\n\nBarrett Values Centre Personal Values Assessment (PVA)\n\nA free assessment that helps you identify your core personal values, the non-negotiables that should be driving your decisions about where to work and what kind of work to pursue. Understanding your values is the foundation of the Clarity work in Lesson 3. Available at valuescentre.com.\n\nCliftonStrengths — Gallup\n\nThe gold standard strengths assessment. CliftonStrengths identifies your dominant talent themes across 34 categories and is the source of the Balconies and Basements framework we cover in Lesson 10B. Knowing your strengths and their shadows, is one of the most useful things you can bring into an interview. Available at gallup.com/cliftonstrengths.\n\nAffintus\n\nA free, externally validated strengths assessment designed specifically to help job seekers understand their competencies, identify transferable skills, and develop the language to describe what they bring to an employer. The report includes phrase stems you can use directly in interviews. Available at affintus.com/job-seekers.\n\nDiSC\n\nA behavioral style assessment that helps you understand how you communicate, how you respond to conflict, and how you work with others. Particularly useful for the Culture dimension of SCOPE and for preparing to answer questions about your leadership and collaboration style. Available at discprofile.com.\n\nLesson 2 — Community: Your Job Search Is a Team Sport\n\nCareer Club Corner\n\nA free weekly job search coaching call open to anyone in transition. Career Club Corner is where the curriculum in this course was developed and refined, in real time, with real job seekers. The community includes a shared networking Google Sheet, accountability partner matching, and a library of recorded sessions. Join us at career.club.\n\nLesson 5 — Your Resume\n\nBriefcase Coach — Sarah Johnston\n\nSarah Johnston is one of the most respected resume and LinkedIn strategists working today. Her guidance on resume construction, particularly on leading with impact, using data, and avoiding the adjective trap, informed the approach in Lesson 5. Her work is worth following closely. Available at briefcasecoach.com.\n\nLesson 10B — Remixing and SCOPE\n\nSCOPE Story Mapping Worksheet\n\nA downloadable spreadsheet that helps you map your twelve STAR stories across the five SCOPE dimensions: Strategy, Culture, Oneself, Passion, and Expertise. Use it to audit your story playlist for gaps and identify which stories to reach for when a particular kind of question comes up. Available at career.club.\n\nLesson 11 — Closing the Deal\n\nRole Evaluation Framework\n\nA downloadable weighted scoring tool that helps you evaluate job opportunities across thirteen dimensions before you’re in the heat of a negotiation. Know your scorecard before the offer arrives, not after. Available at career.club.\n\nSalary.com\n\nThe most widely used source for market compensation data. Use it to research the midpoint for your role, level, function, and geography before any compensation conversation. Available at salary.com.\n\nThe Pivot Engine\n\nIf Making Your Own Weather is the playbook for running a great job search, the Pivot Engine is what you use when you need to rethink the game entirely.\n\nThe job market has changed structurally, not just cyclically. Automation and AI are permanently consolidating roles, and the traditional approach of replacing your last job with an identical title is increasingly a losing strategy. The Pivot Engine is a structured system for career reinvention: a step-by-step process that deconstructs your past experience into universal value, layers in your strengths, values, and passions, and uses AI to generate a menu of opportunities you may never have considered, including consulting, fractional leadership, and entrepreneurial paths, not just traditional employment.\n\nIt is built on a simple but powerful reframe: stop asking who is hiring for what I used to do and start asking where is my specific superpower most needed right now?\n\nThe Pivot Engine is a companion product to this course, available at career.club.\n\nBooks Worth Reading\n\nGetting to Yes — Roger Fisher and William Ury\n\nMany people think of negotiation as a confrontation, a zero-sum tug of war where someone wins and someone loses. This book will change that. Fisher and Ury’s principles are the foundation of everything in Lesson 11: the BATNA concept, the win-win framing, the idea that a fact-based conversation beats a feelings-based one every time. If negotiating makes you uncomfortable, read this book. It is practical, readable, and will change how you think about every negotiation in your life, not just the ones that happen in a job search.\n\nNever Search Alone — Phyl Terry\n\nJob search is a team sport. That's not a platitude. It's the premise of this entire course and it’s the thesis of Phyl Terry’s book. Terry argues that the traditional solo job search is not just inefficient, it’s isolating in a way that actively works against you. His model: building a small, committed peer group to search together, is one of the most practical and psychologically sound approaches to job search I’ve encountered. If the community lessons resonated with you, this book will take that thinking further.\n\nMan’s Search for Meaning — Viktor Frankl\n\nThis is not a job search book. It is something more important. Frankl, a psychiatrist and Holocaust survivor, wrote about the one freedom that can never be taken from us: the freedom to choose how we respond to what happens to us. In the middle of a job search, when the rejection is real and the uncertainty is grinding, that idea is not abstract. It is practical. It is the intellectual foundation of everything we covered in Lesson 1 about attitude, agency, and keeping an even keel. One of the most important books ever written. Everyone should read it at least once.\n\nThe 7 Habits of Highly Effective People — Stephen Covey\n\nCovey’s framework has endured for decades because it works. The habits most relevant to your job search, beginning with the end in mind, thinking win-win, seeking first to understand, show up throughout this course even when they aren’t cited by name. If you want a single book that will make you better at job search and better at everything else in your professional life simultaneously, this is it. It rewards rereading at every stage of a career.";
